{"title_page": "Holiday (Madonna song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1983 single by Madonna}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name           = Holiday\n| type           = single\n| cover          = Madonna Holiday first UK vinyl cover art Golden Arrow montage.jpg\n| caption        = One of UK edition cover arts\n| alt            = The black-and-white picture of the engine of a train. A symbol of a white arrow is present at the center of the engine's front. The words \"Golden Arrow\" are written on the arrow. A couple walks beside the engine on the platform, the man carrying a suitcase. On the top-right corner of the image, the words \"Madonna\" and \"Holiday\" are written in white, on bright red stripes.\n| artist         = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| album          = [[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna]]\n| border         = yes\n| B-side         = \"I Know It\"<br>\"Think of Me\" <small>(UK)</small>\n| released       = September 7, 1983\n| format         = {{hlist|[[Gramophone record|7-inch]]|[[12-inch single|12-inch]]|[[Compact Disc single|CD]]}}\n| recorded       = February 1983\n| studio         = [[Sigma Sound Studios]]<br><small>([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])</small>\n| length         = 6:08\n| label          = {{hlist|[[Sire Records|Sire]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n| genre          = {{hlist|[[Dance-pop]]|[[post-disco]]}}\n| writer         = {{hlist|Curtis Hudson|Lisa Stevens}}\n| producer       = [[John \"Jellybean\" Benitez]]\n| prev_title     = [[Burning Up (Madonna song)|Burning Up]]\n| prev_year      = 1983\n| next_title     = [[Lucky Star (Madonna song)|Lucky Star]]\n| next_year      = 1983\n| misc           =\n}}\n\n\"'''Holiday'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for her eponymous debut [[album]] ''[[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna]]'' (1983). [[Sire Records]] released it as the album's third single on September 7, 1983. \"Holiday\" later appeared remixed on the remix compilation ''[[You Can Dance]]'' (1987) and the greatest hits compilation ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'' (1990), and in its original form on the greatest hits album ''[[Celebration (Madonna album)|Celebration]]'' (2009).\n\nWritten by Curtis Hudson and Lisa Stevens of [[Pure Energy (band)|Pure Energy]], the track was offered to Madonna by her producer [[John \"Jellybean\" Benitez]] when she was looking for a potential hit track to include on her debut album. After accepting the song, she and Benitez worked on it and altered its composition by the addition of a piano solo performed by their friend, [[Fred Zarr]].\n\n\"Holiday\" features instrumentation from guitars, electronic handclaps, a cowbell, and a synthesized string arrangement, while its lyrics speak about the universal sentiment of taking a holiday. Universally acclaimed by [[Music journalism|critics]], the song became Madonna's first mainstream [[hit single]] in the United States, peaking at number 16 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It also became her first top-ten single in several countries, including Australia, Belgium, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom. Madonna has performed \"Holiday\" on most of her tours and it is generally included as a part of the encore. Different performances of the song are included in the recorded releases of her tours. \"Holiday\" has been covered by several artists and appeared in multiple television shows. In 2003, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q Magazine]]'' ranked \"Holiday\" at number 88 in their list of the \"1001 Best Songs Ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muzieklijstjes.nl/Q1001bestsongsever.htm|title=Q - 1001 best songs ever (2003)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background and writing==\nIn 1983, 25-year-old Madonna was recording her eponymous debut album with [[Warner Bros. Records]] producer [[Reggie Lucas]], after [[Sire Records]] green-lit it when her first single \"[[Everybody (Madonna song)|Everybody]]\" became a club hit.<ref>{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=9}}</ref> However, she did not have enough material for the album.<ref name=\"rikky1\">{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=10}}</ref> Lucas brought two new songs to the project and [[John \"Jellybean\" Benitez]], a DJ at Funhouse disco was called to remix the available tracks. In the meantime due to a conflict of interest, Madonna's collaborator on \"Everybody\", [[Stephen Bray]] had sold a song \"Ain't No Big Deal\" to an act called Barracuda on another label, rendering it unavailable for Madonna's album.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/> It was Benitez who discovered a new song written by Curtis Hudson and Lisa Stevens of the pop group [[Pure Energy (band)|Pure Energy]].<ref name=\"cross1\">{{harvnb|Cross|2007|p=26}}</ref> The song, titled \"Holiday\", had been turned down by singers [[Phyllis Hyman]] and [[Mary Wilson (singer)|Mary Wilson]], formerly of [[The Supremes]].<ref name=\"morton1\">{{harvnb|Morton|2002|p=158}}</ref> Hudson and Stevens were asked by Benitez if they had any song for then-unknown Madonna and since their record label [[Prism Records|Prism]] did not want to release \"Holiday\", they gave it to Benitez. Pure Energy recalled in an interview with [[Blogcritics]]:\n<blockquote>\nWe knew that the song had that magic to it. Since we weren't going to be able to record [\"Holiday\"] ourselves, we were really hoping it would fall into the hands of someone who was going to do it justice. Jellybean was shopping it, and I think he pitched it to Phyllis Hyman and a couple of other artists. We didn't pitch the songs that much. I was still hoping we could come around to Pure Energy recording it.<ref name=\"blog\"/>\n</blockquote>\nStevens remembered that she had started playing the beginning chords of \"Holiday\" on a keyboard but could not progress further. Hudson, who felt that the music could lead to something constructive, urged Stevens to experiment with it for a week and ultimately came up with the hook \"Holiday, Celebrate!\", while going back-and-forth between them. Inspired by the opening chords and hearing depressing news on the radio, Hudson started penning down the song and within 30 minutes was able to complete it, with the whole composition and arrangement in his mind. Most of the song was written by him with Stevens suggesting few alterations like the line \"It would be so nice\".<ref name=\"blog\">{{cite web|url=https://blogcritics.org/interview-curtis-hudson-lisa-stevens-songwriters/|title=Interview: Curtis Hudson & Lisa Stevens, Songwriters of Madonna's 'Holiday'|last=Kantor|first=Justin|date=February 1, 2012|accessdate=May 19, 2018|publisher=[[Blogcritics]]}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and composition==\nBenitez and Madonna sent the [[demo (music)|demo]] to their friend, [[Fred Zarr]] so he could change the arrangement and program it differently. After the vocals were added by Madonna, Benitez spent four days and tried to enhance the commercial appeal of the track before the April 1983 deadline set by Madonna's record label.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/><ref name=\"morton1\"/> Benitez had not [[record producer|produced]] any song at that time but was aware of how to reconstruct the different musical pieces in a studio. He composed the sound, assembled the musicians and hummed the tune to them for recording. He also asked Madonna to sing in a \"soulful\" manner on the track.<ref>{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|p=109}}</ref> Just before it was completed, Madonna and Benitez met Zarr at [[Sigma Sound Studios]] in Manhattan where the track was recorded. The singer suggested Zarr to add a piano solo towards the end of the track, as well as asked Hudson to change a part of the funk in the guitar rhythm.<ref name=\"cross1\"/>\n\n{{listen\n | filename     = Madonna-holiday.ogg\n | title        = \"Holiday\"\n | pos          = left\n | description  = A sample of \"Holiday\" featuring its repetitive [[refrain|chorus]] and the four bar sequence in its musical composition\n}}\nPure Energy, who were also present at the recording studio during February 1983,<ref name=\"liner\"/> recalled that the rhythm track was finished in a single day because they did not want to venture further from the demo track. Minor changes were included, like substituting Hudson's [[LinnDrum]] with Zarr's [[Oberheim DMX]]. Other changes were in the vocal delivery from the soul, gospel like singing on the demo to Madonna's \"poppier\" belting; she still remained true to the original melody of the track. The group was not given a production credit on \"Holiday\" since Benitez had presented the track to Sire Records, and he had an existing relationship with Madonna. Although Hudson pressed for a credit, they ultimately let it go since they felt that the song would be their chance to get recognized as efficient songwriters.<ref name=\"blog\"/>\n\nMusically, \"Holiday\" is a [[dance-pop]] and [[post-disco]] song devoid of any particular structure.<ref name=\"Sullivan2013\">{{cite book|first=Steve|last=Sullivan|title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings|year=2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8296-6|pages=336}}</ref> It begins with a chord sequence reminiscent of [[Cyndi Lauper]]'s \"[[Time After Time (Cyndi Lauper song)|Time After Time]]\" (1984).<ref name=\"rikky2\"/> Set in the [[time signature]] of common time with a medium [[tempo]] of 116 [[beats per minute]], the song is composed in the key of [[D major]] and is six minutes seven seconds in length. Madonna's vocal range spans from B<sub>3</sub> to C{{music|sharp}}<sub>5</sub>. The track follows in the [[chord progression]] of G\u2013A\u2013Bm in the first line, when Madonna sings \"Holiday!\" and changes to G\u2013A\u2013F{{music|sharp}}m\u2013G in the second line, when Madonna sings \"Celebrate!\".<ref name=\"sheet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0037594|title=Madonna 'Holiday' Sheet Music|publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Alfred Music Publishing|Alfred Publishing]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|date=November 13, 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe four bar sequence of the progression continues throughout the song and features instrumentation from guitars flicking in the background, electronic handclaps, [[cowbell (instrument)|cowbell]] played by Madonna, and a synthesized string arrangement.<ref name=\"rikky2\"/> A side-by-side repetitive progression is achieved by making use of the [[refrain|chorus]]. Towards the end of the song, a change in the arrangement happens, where a piano [[Break (music)|break]] is heard. Lyrically the song expresses the universal sentiment that everybody needs a holiday from their daily lives.<ref name=\"rikky2\"/> Along with Benitez's production and Zarr's instrumentation, other personnel working on \"Holiday\" included Raymond Hudson on [[bass (sound)|bass]], Bashiri Johnson on [[percussion instrument|percussion]] and Tina B. and Norma Jean Wright who provided background vocals.<ref name=\"liner\">{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna]]|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=LP, Vinyl, CD|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=9 23867-1}}</ref>\n\n==Release details==\nInitially it was decided that \"[[Lucky Star (Madonna song)|Lucky Star]]\" would be released as a single; instead \"Holiday\" was released in the United States when the latter was picked up by radios for airplay and became a dance hit.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/> Warner Bros. Records were not prepared for the song to take off like that and hence no music video was released for it.<ref name=\"blog\"/> The original British cover art for \"Holiday\" did not carry Madonna's picture since Sire did not want the British people to find out that she was not a R&B artist. Instead it carried the picture of a train station and an engine.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/> \"Holiday\" was later remixed in [[Dub music|dub]] and [[Groove (music)|groove]] versions for the 1987 remix album ''[[You Can Dance]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r12207|pure_url=yes}}|title= You Can Dance > Overview|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=August 4, 1987|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> It also appeared in her first greatest hits compilation, ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'', in a remixed and shortened form.<ref>{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=11}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Holiday\" has been released three times as a single: in January 1984, reaching number six; reissued in August 1985, reaching number 2 (only being kept from number one by her own \"[[Into the Groove]]\" single); and re-released with new artwork in 1991 to promote ''The Immaculate Collection'' with a limited edition EP titled ''[[The Immaculate Collection#The Holiday Collection|The Holiday Collection]]'', which contained tracks omitted from the compilation; this version reached number five. Although the song was released to promote the greatest hits collection, it did not include the shorter remix from the album, instead it included the original album version from ''Madonna'' (1983).<ref name=\"uk\"/> The photography used for the 1991 release was by [[Steven Meisel]] and had previously been used for the February 1991 cover for ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' Italia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.it/en/people-are-talking-about/obsession-of-the-day/2011/12/madonna-superbowl-meisel|title=Madonna Come Marilyn|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] Italia|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\nIt has been featured in [[Wii]] dance video game ''[[Just Dance 2]]'' .\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Madonna 5 (24527521109) (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Madonna performing \"Holiday\" as the encore of the [[Rebel Heart Tour]] in 2015|alt=Madonna in a red hat and blue jacket with a red-and-blue flag wrapped around her performing onstage]]\nAuthor Rikky Rooksby in his book ''The Complete Guide to the Music of Madonna'' commented that \"'Holiday' was as infectious as the plague. One listen and you could not get the damn [[Hook (music)|hook]] out of your mind.\" He also likened the track as getting on a [[carousel]] and enjoying the ride, or get really bothered by the song going \"on-and-on\" for six minutes.<ref name=\"rikky2\">{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=13}}</ref> Jim Farber of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' commented that \"Holiday\" satisfied the musical ear of both the sides of the Atlantic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,255548,00.html|title=The Girl Material|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=July 27, 2001|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> While reviewing ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'' album, [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] from ''Entertainment Weekly'' commented that \"Holiday\" was a \"spunky dance-beat trifle\". He also complimented the song's expert production.<ref>{{cite web|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|title=Madonna: The Immaculate Collection|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318856,00.html|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=December 14, 1990|accessdate=March 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\nMary Cross in her biography of Madonna, described \"Holiday\" as \"a simple song with a fresh appeal and a good mood.\"<ref name=\"cross2\">{{harvnb|Cross|2007|p=27}}</ref> According to author [[Lucy O'Brien]], who wrote in the biography ''[[Madonna: Like an Icon]]'', the track was an example of Madonna's early musical endeavors being about the \"power of dance\". She believed that the song cemented her style of music with its \"bubbling Latin undertow, crunchy bass and strings and Fred Zarr's elegant closing piano riff\". O'Brien declared \"Holiday\" as Madonna's \"most\" persuasive dance song with its \"tension, release, resolution and celebratory\" nature enhanced by Madonna's \"playful commands and exhortations\".<ref>{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|pp=106\u2013107}}</ref> Sal Cinquemani of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' described the song as airy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-madonna-remaster|title=Madonna (Remastered): Review|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=September 9, 2001|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] from [[AllMusic]] called it effervescent and one of the great songs of the ''Madonna'' album.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r12203|pure_url=yes}}|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|title= Madonna > Overview|date=June 10, 1983|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> While reviewing ''The Immaculate Collection'', he called it one of her greatest hits.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r12210|pure_url=yes}}|title= The Immaculate Collection > Overview|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=December 12, 1990|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> Don Shewey of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' commented that the simple lyrics of the song sound clever.<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/reviews/album/3045/21667|title=Madonna: Madonna album review|last=Shewey|first=Don|date=September 25, 1983|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n[[File:HolidayRIT (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Madonna performing \"Holiday\" on the [[Re-Invention World Tour]] (2004)]]\n\"Holiday\" was released on September 7, 1983, and became Madonna's first hit single in the United States and remained on the charts from Thanksgiving to Christmas 1983.<ref name=\"morton1\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Grein|first=Paul|title=Chart Beat|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ziQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT5&dq=Madonna+Holiday+single+release+September+1983|date=February 2, 1985|accessdate=March 10, 2013|journal=Billboard|page=6|issn=0006-2510|volume=97|issue=5}}</ref> It was Madonna's first song to enter the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], at 88 on the issue dated October 29, 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1983-10-29/hot-100?order=gainer|title=The Billboard Hot 100: Week Ending October 29, 1983|date=October 29, 1983|accessdate=July 3, 2009|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> and reached a peak of 16 on January 28, 1984 and was on the chart for 21 weeks.<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1984-01-28/hot-100?order=timeon|title=The Billboard Hot 100: Week Ending January 28, 1984|date=January 28, 1984|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 26, 2011}}</ref> The song debuted at eight on the [[Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart on the issue dated November 2, 1983 and was Madonna's first number one single on the Hot Dance Club Play chart remaining at the top for five weeks.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/><ref name=\"amgbb\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=madonna-r12203/charts-awards/billboard-single|pure_url=yes}}|title= Madonna > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles |publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> The song also made an entry in the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart and peaked at 25, remaining on the chart for 20 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/r-b-hip-hop-songs?chartDate=1983-11-17&order=timeon|title=''Billboard'' Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs: Week Ending November 19, 1983|date=November 19, 1983|work=Billboard|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> In Canada, the song debuted at number 48 position of the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' singles chart on January 21, 1984<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4430&volume=39&issue=20&issue_dt=January%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 4430|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022014719/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4430&volume=39&issue=20&issue_dt=January%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and peaked at number 39.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8308&volume=39&issue=25&issue_dt=February%2025%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 8308|work=RPM|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022014558/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8308&volume=39&issue=25&issue_dt=February%2025%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The song again entered the chart at number 45 in March 1984,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6277&volume=40&issue=2&issue_dt=March%2017%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 6277|work=RPM|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022015344/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6277&volume=40&issue=2&issue_dt=March%2017%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and peaked at number 32 in April 1984.<ref name=\"can\"/> It was present on the chart for a total of 12 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6703&volume=40&issue=7&issue_dt=April%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 6703|work=RPM|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010154742/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6703&volume=40&issue=7&issue_dt=April%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 10, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Holiday\" was released in 1984 whence it charted and reached a peak of six on the chart. However, a rerelease in 1985 with \"Think of Me\" on the B-side, saw the song enter the charts at number&nbsp;32 and reached a new peak of two on the chart, being held off the number one spot by Madonna's own \"[[Into the Groove]]\", while being present for ten weeks. Another re-release in 1991 saw the song reach a peak of five on the chart.<ref name=\"uk\"/> The song was certified gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) in August 1985,<ref name=\"bpi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|title=BPI \u2013 Certified Awards Search|date=August 1, 1983|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> and according to the [[Official Charts Company]], \"Holiday\" has sold 718,000 copies there as of August 2017.<ref name=\"uksales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/madonna-s-official-top-40-biggest-selling-singles__8266/|title=Open your chart to me... Madonna's Official Top 40 Biggest Selling Singles|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=August 16, 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Across Europe, the song reached the top ten of Belgium, Netherlands, Germany and Ireland<ref name=\"bel\"/><ref name=\"dutch\"/><ref name=\"german\"/><ref name=\"irish\"/> while reaching the top 40 in France, Sweden and Switzerland.<ref name=\"france\"/><ref name=\"sweden\"/><ref name=\"swiss\"/> According to ''[[Music & Media]]'' magazine the song had sold around 1.5&nbsp;million copies in Europe by September 1985.<ref name=\"eurosales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Music-Media-IDX/IDX/80s/85/M&M-1985-09-23-OCR-Page-0008.pdf|title=Madonna Mania Now Spreading All Over Europe|date=September 23, 1985|accessdate=June 10, 2018|work=[[Music & Media]]}}</ref> \"Holiday\" reached top five on the [[Kent Music Report]] chart of Australia.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> The song debuted at number 37 on the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]], making it Madonna's debut chart appearance in the country. It peaked at number seven.<ref name=\"sweden\"/>\n\nDuring a 2005 interview with Harry Smith of [[CBS News]], Madonna singled out \"Holiday\" as a favorite amongst her top-ten charting singles, though Smith corrected that it had peaked at a much lower position.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/12/13/earlyshow/leisure/celebspot/main1121578.shtml|title=Madonna, Elvis Alike In Key Way|last=Dakss|first=Brian|date=December 13, 2005|accessdate=July 3, 2009|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> Pure Energy remembered that the success of \"Holiday\" also helped them financially, the royalties helping them move out of the [[boarding house]] they had been living. Hudson confirmed that the song still generated money for them, saying that \"Can you live off of one hit? Yes, you can if you get the right hit. It can last you a lifetime. We've been living proof of that\". However, the band were not able to replicate their songwriting success of \"Holiday\" with later releases, since the music business still expected them to concoct something like the track.<ref name=\"blog\"/>\n\n==Live performances==\nMadonna has performed \"Holiday\" on almost all of her tours, namely [[The Virgin Tour]], [[Who's That Girl World Tour|Who's That Girl]], [[Blond Ambition World Tour|Blond Ambition]], [[The Girlie Show World Tour|The Girlie Show]], [[Drowned World Tour|Drowned World]], [[Re-Invention World Tour|Re-Invention]], [[Sticky & Sweet Tour]] and [[Rebel Heart Tour]]. In 1984, Madonna performed Holiday on the hit dance show ''[[American Bandstand]]'' with [[Dick Clark]].<ref name=\"cross2\"/> Madonna then added it to the set list of her 1985 Virgin Tour. It was performed as the second song of the tour.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=42}}</ref> The same year she performed the song at the [[Live Aid]] benefit concert in Philadelphia in July.<ref name=\"voller1\">{{harvnb|Voller|1999|p=56}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HolidayUnderGround2 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Madonna performing \"Holiday\" on the [[Blond Ambition World Tour]] in 1990|alt=Madonna in a polka dotted blouse and white pants singing onstage]]\nThe Who's That Girl World Tour in 1987 had Madonna performing \"Holiday\" as the last song of the tour. Madonna performed an energetic version of the song, signalling the celebratory and wholesome nature of the song's theme.<ref>{{harvnb|Kellner|1995|p=276}}</ref> She sang the final chorus twice, and on some dates asked the audience for a comb so that she could fix her hair and finished the performance.<ref name=\"ciao\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[Ciao Italia: Live from Italy]]|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1988}}</ref> Two different performances are found in ''[[Ciao Italia: Live from Italy]]'' tour video filmed at [[Stadio Olimpico di Torino|Stadio Communale]] in [[Turin]], Italy on September 4, 1987<ref name=\"ciao\"/> and the ''Who's That Girl: Live in Japan'' tour video filmed at [[Korakuen Stadium]] in [[Tokyo]], Japan on June 22, 1987.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Who's That Girl&nbsp;\u2013 Live in Japan|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1987}}</ref>\n\nFor the Blond Ambition World Tour in 1990, Madonna said, \"I wanted to throw an old song for fun, and 'Holiday' seemed to be a universal favourite. In addition to that it's one of the only old songs I've done that I can still sing and not feel I've totally outgrown it.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Michael|2004|p=52}}</ref> Performing it as a part of the encore, Madonna appeared on the stage in a polka-dotted blouse with matching flounces at the bottom of white trousers and hair in a top knot with a ponytail.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=84}}</ref> The costume was adopted from a ''[[My Fair Lady (film)|My Fair Lady]]'' dress and was designed by [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]]. Three different performances are found in the ''Blond Ambition: Japan Tour 90'' VHS, the ''[[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]'' VHS and the ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare|Truth or Dare]]'' documentary. The performance included in the documentary was used as a music video to promote it.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Blond Ambition: Japan Tour 90|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Truth or Dare|last=Goodlum|first=Jeff|date=December 4, 2000|journal=Rolling Stone|volume=1079|issue=19|issn=0035-791X}}</ref> The performance received four nominations at the [[1992 MTV Video Music Awards]], including Best Female Video, Best Dance Video, Best Choreography in Video and Best Cinematography in Video, but did not win any of the categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1992/|title=MTV Video Music Awards&nbsp;\u2013 1992&nbsp;\u2013 Highlights, Winners, Performers|publisher=[[MTV]]|accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn The Girlie Show in 1993, the song was performed in an alternate version as the second-to-last song of the tour.<ref name=\"gs\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[The Girlie Show: Live Down Under]]|type=DVD|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1993}}</ref> It had a military theme to it.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=139}}</ref> Halfway through the performance Madonna paused the song for a military drill with the dancers and the audience.<ref name=\"lull\">{{harvnb|Lull|Hinerman|1997|p=250}}</ref> The performance met with strong reaction in Puerto Rico, when Madonna rubbed the Puerto Rican national flag between her legs in between the performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3704915.stm|title=Show-stealer Madonna on tour|last=Smith|first=Neil|date=May 24, 2004|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref> For the Drowned World Tour in 2001 Madonna wore a fur coat, velvet fedora and a customised [[Dolce & Gabbana]] T-shirt which proclaimed 'Mother' in the front and 'F*cker' in the back painted in silver. This demonstrated her ghetto-girl appearance adopted for the song's performance.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=174}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sticky-holiday-MJ-tribute.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Michael Jackson]] tribute during \"Holiday\" on the [[Sticky & Sweet Tour]] shows in 2009]]\nIn the Re-Invention Tour in 2004, the song was again performed as the ending song of the tour.<ref name=tim>{{harvnb|Timmerman|2007|p=47}}</ref> The song was given a tribal feeling with Madonna wearing Scottish kilts during the performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,640170,00.html|title=Madonna's Wardrobe Ready for Reinvention|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=April 3, 2004|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> The performance started with Madonna and her dancers doing a dance routine in front of the stage, then Madonna going on the revolving tiers of the stage to sing the song as confetti fell from above.<ref name=tim/> The performance was included in the ''[[I'm Going to Tell You a Secret]]'' live album and documentary.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[I'm Going to Tell You a Secret]]|type=DVD|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=2005}}</ref> Stephen Thomas Erlewine of Allmusic commented that the performance \"feels like they could fit the Eurotrash, campy retro-disco feel of [[Confessions Tour|Confessions]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r834380|pure_url=yes}}|title=I'm Going to Tell You a Secret > Overview |last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=September 9, 2006|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe song was added to the 2009 leg of her Sticky & Sweet Tour. It replaced the song \"Heartbeat\" from ''[[Hard Candy (Madonna album)|Hard Candy]]'' and was used as a tribute to singer [[Michael Jackson]] who died a week prior to the start of the second leg of the tour.<ref name=\"Madonna's Michael Jackson Tribute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Madonnas_Emotional_Onstage_Tribute_to_Jackson/5664629|title=Madonna's Emotional Onstage Tribute to Jackson|publisher=Hollywood.com|accessdate=July 5, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706064807/http://www.hollywood.com/news/Madonnas_Emotional_Onstage_Tribute_to_Jackson/5664629|archivedate=July 6, 2009|date=July 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"sticky\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-07-06/entertainment/0907060107_1_michael-jackson-impersonator-madonna|title=Madonna pays tribute to Michael Jackson in concert|last=Saad|first=Nardeen|date=July 5, 2009|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref> As Madonna sang the song, a picture of a young Jackson appeared on stage, followed by a Jackson impersonator wearing garments in Jackson style.<ref name=\"sticky\"/> The music then switched to a medley of his songs, like \"[[Billie Jean]]\" and \"[[Wanna Be Startin' Somethin']]\", and the impersonator worked through his moves, including the [[Moonwalk (dance)|moonwalk]] as well as the spinning and gyrating.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1615279/20090705/madonna.jhtml|title=Madonna Salutes Michael Jackson At London's O2 Arena|last=Rodriquez|first=Jason|date=July 5, 2009|accessdate=July 6, 2009|publisher=MTV News}}</ref> Madonna clapped her hands, swayed from side to side and jumped up and down while images of Jackson over the years flashed on a big screen.<ref name=\"mtv\"/> After the performance, Madonna told the crowd, \"Let's give it up for one of the greatest artists the world has ever known,\" and the crowd applauded.<ref name=\"sticky\"/>\n\nIn 2012, Madonna performed \"Holiday\" on some shows of [[The MDNA Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ganz|first=Caryn|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/09/madonna-mdna-tour-yankee-stadium-review/|title=Act of God: Madonna's MDNA Tour Comes to Yankee Stadium|date=September 10, 2012|accessdate=April 15, 2019|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]}}</ref> The song was the closing number to Madonna's [[Rebel Heart Tour]] in 2015\u20132016, it included an excerpt from [[Bob James (musician)|Bob James]]' cover of \"[[Take Me to the Mardi Gras]]\".<ref name=\"videorebel\"/> She performed the song while she's wrapped with the country's flag. She exits from stage while she's levitated by a harness and rope.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2015/09/rebel-heart-tour-madonna-takes-the-verizon-center-by-storm-review/|title=Madonna Takes The Verizon Center by Storm: Review|date=September 9, 2015|accessdate=September 17, 2017|work=Metro Weekly}}</ref> The performance was included in the live album ''[[Rebel Heart Tour (album)|Rebel Heart Tour]]'' recorded in Sydney, Australia, and released in September 2017.<ref name=\"videorebel\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[Rebel Heart Tour (album)|Rebel Heart Tour]]|medium=2\u00d7 CD, DVD, Blu-ray|publisher=Eagle Records|year=2017}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Covers and media appearance==\n{{See also|List of cover versions of Madonna songs|List of Madonna tribute albums}}\n\nBritish [[synthpop]] band [[Heaven 17]] recorded a cover for the 1999 compilation ''Virgin Voices Vol. 1: A Tribute To Madonna''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4467|pure_url=yes}}|title=Heaven 17 > Overview |last=Ankeny|first=Jason|date=October 28, 1999|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> In 2002, Mad'House recorded a [[Electronic dance music|Club]] cover of the song for their album ''Absolutely Mad''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r606622|pure_url=yes}}|title=Absolutely Mad > Overview|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=August 9, 2009}}</ref> [[Girl Authority]] covered the song in 2007 for their album, ''[[Road Trip (Girl Authority album)|Road Trip]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmv.com.hk/product/rockpop.asp?sku=720230|title=Girl Authority&nbsp;\u2013 Roadtrip|publisher=[[HMV Group]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924031157/http://www.hmv.com.hk/product/rockpop.asp?sku=720230|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1986, Dutch rap duo [[MC Miker G & DJ Sven]] released \"[[Holiday Rap]]\", a song which sampled the tune and chorus of Madonna's \"Holiday\". It achieved commercial success by peaking the charts in countries like France, Netherlands and Switzerland and going the top ten of Austria, Norway, Britain and Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/en/showitem.asp?interpret=M%2EC%2E+Miker+%27G%27+%26+Deejay+Sven&titel=Holiday+Rap&cat=s|title=M.C. Miker and Deejay Sven&nbsp;\u2013 Holiday Rap (Song)|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> The bassline of the song was [[sampling (music)|sampled]] by [[The Avalanches]] for their 2000 album ''[[Since I Left You]]''. It was used on the songs \"Stay Another Season\" and \"Little Journey\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/a/avalanches-since.shtml|title=The Avalanches: Since I Left You < Reviews|last=Hseigh|first=Christine|date=November 6, 2001|work=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe song was redone by the ''[[Will & Grace]]'' cast as \"He's Hot\" for the sitcom's soundtrack in 2004 and even includes vocal samples from Madonna herself. Almost all of the instrumental part of the song \"He's Hot!\" uses samples from the original song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12178639|title='Will & Grace' Compilation Album in Works|last=Hay|first=Carla|date=July 17, 2004|publisher=Yahoo! Music Canada|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> The Canadian teen drama ''[[Degrassi: The Next Generation]]'', which is known for naming each episode after an 80s hit song, named a two-part episode after \"Holiday\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/degrassi-the-next-generation/holiday-1/episode/278919/summary.html|title=Degrassi: The Next Generation: Holiday (1)|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/degrassi-the-next-generation/holiday-2/episode/278921/summary.html|title=Degrassi: The Next Generation: Holiday (2)|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> In 2006, critics noted strong similarity between \"Holiday\" and American singer [[Jessica Simpson]]'s single \"[[A Public Affair (song)|A Public Affair]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/25/AR2006082500226.html|title=Two Divas: One Has No Shame (Or Talent)|first=Allison|last=Stewart|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 27, 2006|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/1092655881.html?dids=1092655881:1092655881&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+10%2C+2006&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=They%27re+baaa-aaack&pqatl=google|title=They're baaa-aaack|work=Chicago Tribune|date=August 10, 2006|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> When criticized for its unoriginality, Simpson told [[MTV]]: \"I think people are ready to hear something that Madonna used to do. We all need to hear that every now and again. It wasn't a sample or something I meant to do, but she did influence me and still does today.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1537645/jessica-covers-song-that-helped-her-let-nick-go.jhtml|title=Jessica Simpson Covers Song That Convinced Her To Let Nick Go|first=Corey|last=Moss|publisher=MTV News|date=August 2, 2006|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> In 2008, \"Holiday\" appeared on the video game ''[[Karaoke Revolution]] Presents: American Idol Encore''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.cube.ign.com/articles/666/666541p1.html|title=Karaoke Revolution Party: Good times never seemed so good.|last=Miller|first=Jonathan|date=November 15, 2005|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930073707/http://uk.cube.ign.com/articles/666/666541p1.html|archivedate=September 30, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Kelis]] often performs a [[Mashup (music)|mashup]] of her own hit \"[[Milkshake (song)|Milkshake]]\" with \"Holiday\" live. In 2003, a snippet of the song appeared in the film ''[[Rugrats Go Wild]]'', when the families went on their [[cruise ship|cruise]].<ref>{{cite AV media|year=2003|title=Rugrats Go Wild|accessdate=February 23, 2013|type=DVD|time=|publisher=[[Nickelodeon Movies]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom Inc]]}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''US / EU 7\" single'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=US 7-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=7-29478}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=European 7-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=92.9478-7}}</ref>\n#\"Holiday\" (7\" Version/Edit)&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n#\"I Know It\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:45\n\n*'''EU 12\" single'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=US 12-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=GSRE 0494}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=European 12-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=92-0176-0}}</ref>\n#\"Holiday\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2013 6:07\n#\"I Know It\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:45\n\n*'''UK 7\" single'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=UK 7-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=929405-7}}</ref>\n#\"Holiday\" (7\" Version/Edit)&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n#\"Think of Me\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:55\n\n*'''UK 12\" single'''<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=UK 12-inch Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=920 173-0}}</ref>\n#\"Holiday\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2013 6:07\n#\"Think of Me\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:53\n\n*'''UK 7\" / 12\" picture disc / Cassette single (1991)'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1991|type=UK 7\", 12\" Picture Disc and Cassette Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=W0037, W0037TP, W0037C/5439-19265-4}}</ref>\n#\"Holiday\" (7\" Edit)&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n#\"[[True Blue (Madonna song)|True Blue]]\" (album version)&nbsp;\u2013 4:17\n\n{{col-2}}\n*'''UK 12\" single (1991)'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Holiday|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1991|type=UK 12\" Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=W0037T, 9362-40098-0}}</ref>\n#\"Holiday\" (album version)&nbsp;\u2013 6:09\n#\"Where's the Party\" (''You Can Dance'' remix edit)&nbsp;\u2013 4:22\n#\"[[Everybody (Madonna song)|Everybody]]\" (''You Can Dance'' remix edit)&nbsp;\u2013 4:57\n\n*'''UK cassette / ''The Holiday Collection'' (1991)'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[The Holiday Collection (EP)|The Holiday Collection]]|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1991|type=UK EP Single liner notes|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=W0037CT, W0037 CD/9362-40099-2}}</ref>\n#\"Holiday\" (album version)&nbsp;\u2013 6:09\n#\"True Blue\" (album version)&nbsp;\u2013 4:17\n#\"[[Who's That Girl (Madonna song)|Who's That Girl]]\" (album version)&nbsp;\u2013 3:58\n#\"[[Causing a Commotion]]\" (Silver Screen Single Mix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:06\n\n*'''Germany 12\" / CD / UK CD single (1995)<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n#\"Holiday\"&nbsp;\u2013 6:07\n#\"Lucky Star\"&nbsp;\u2013 5:37\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from the album liner notes.<ref name=\"liner\"/>\n*[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, cowbell\n*Curtis Hudson&nbsp;\u2013 songwriter, guitars\n*Lisa Stevens&nbsp;\u2013 songwriter\n*[[John \"Jellybean\" Benitez]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer\n*[[Fred Zarr]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Programming (music)|drum programming]], [[moog bass]], synthesizer, acoustic piano\n*Raymond Hudson&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass (sound)|bass]]\n*Bashiri Johnson&nbsp;\u2013 percussion\n*Tina B.&nbsp;\u2013 background vocals\n*Norma Jean Wright&nbsp;\u2013 background vocals\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1983\u201391)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|type=doc|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book, St Ives, N.S.W|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6|title-link=Kent Music Report}}</ref>\n|4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|6|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|refname=\"bel\"|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|32|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|chartid=6316|refname=\"can\"|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|37|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"france\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|9|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|songid=1104|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 19, 2018|refname=\"german\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|2|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"irish\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|7|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"dutch\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|7|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"nz\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|20|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"sweden\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|18|artist=Madonna|song=Holiday|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"swiss\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|6|artist=Madonna|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"uk\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|2|artist=Madonna|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"uk\"|note=1985 Re-Release}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|5|artist=Madonna|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"uk\"|note=1991 Re-Release}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|16|artist=Madonna|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"bbhot100\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|1|artist=Madonna|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"bbdance\"|note=with \"Lucky Star\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|25|artist=Madonna|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 27, 2014|refname=\"bbrb\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Zimbabwe ([[List of record charts|ZIMA]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Kimberley |first=Christopher |title=Zimbabwe Singles Chart Book: 1965\u20131996}}</ref><br/><small>''1991 Release''</small>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (1984)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia (Kent Music Report)<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n|33\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1984|title=Top 100 Single-Jahrescharts|language=German|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment]]|accessdate=December 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|74\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"yearendbb\">{{cite journal|title=Hot 100 Year end issue: 1984|date=December 22, 1984|accessdate=April 3, 2013|journal=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZSQEAAAAMBAJ|page=14|issn=0006-2510|volume=96|issue=51}}</ref>\n|79\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Dance Club Songs (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"yearendbb\"/><br>{{small|''with \"Lucky Star\"''}}\n|25\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certification and sales==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n!scope=\"row\"|South Africa ([[RISA]])\n|Gold<ref name=\"southafrica\">{{cite news|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/80s/1984/BB-1984-06-02.pdf|title=LADY MADONNA|date=June 2, 1984|work=Billboard|access-date=April 4, 2020|page=6}}</ref>\n|20,000<sup>^</sup>\n|-\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|title=Holiday|artist=Madonna|award=Gold|relyear=1984|salesamount=878,000|salesref=<ref name=\"uk sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/madonnas-top-20-biggest-songs-on-the-official-chart__23721/|title=Madonna Top 20 biggest songs on the official chart|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=25 August 2018|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>}}|refname=\"bpi\"|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}\n|-\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States| title=Holiday|artist=Madonna|nocert=true |type=single|award=|relyear=1998|salesref=<ref name=\"Madonna Ask Billboard\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/958389/ask-billboard-glee-ful-about-madonna|title=Ask Billboard: 'Glee'-ful About Madonna|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=April 30, 2010|work=Billboard|access-date=April 22, 2012}}</ref>|salesamount=260,000 (digital only)}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Madonna (album)}}\n*[[List of number-one dance singles of 1983 (U.S.)]]\n*[[List of UK top 10 singles in 1985]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n*{{Citation|last=Clerk|first=Carol|title=Madonnastyle|year=2002|publisher=[[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]]|isbn=0-7119-8874-9}}\n*{{Citation|last=Cross|first=Mary|title=Madonna: A Biography|year=2007|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|isbn=978-0-313-33811-3}}\n*{{Citation|last=Kellner|first=Douglas|title=Media Culture: Cultural Studies, Identity, and Politics Between the Modern and the Postmodern|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=1995|authorlink=Douglas Kellner|isbn=0-415-10570-6}}\n*{{Citation|last=Lull|first=James|first2=Stephen|last2=Hinerman|title=Media scandals: morality and desire in the popular culture marketplace|year=1997|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|isbn=0-231-11165-7}}\n*{{Citation|last=Michael|first=Mick St.|title=Madonna 'talking': Madonna in Her Own Words|year=2004|publisher=[[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]]|isbn=1-84449-418-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/madonnatalkingma0000stmi}}\n*{{Citation|last=Morton|first=Andrew|title=Madonna|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|year=2002|isbn=0-312-98310-7|authorlink=Andrew Morton (writer)}}\n*{{cite book|last=O'Brien|first=Lucy|title=Madonna: Like an Icon|year=2008|authorlink=Lucy O'Brien|publisher=[[Bantam Press]]|isbn=978-0-552-15361-4|ref=harv|title-link=Madonna: Like an Icon}}\n*{{Citation|last=Rooksby|first=Rikky|title=The Complete Guide to the Music of Madonna|year=2004|publisher=[[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]]|isbn=0-7119-9883-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/madonnacompleteg0000rook}}\n*{{Citation|last=Timmerman|first=Dirk|title=Madonna Live! Secret Re-inventions and Confessions on Tour|year=2007|publisher=Maklu Publications Inc|isbn=978-90-8595-002-8}}\n*{{Citation|last=Voller|first=Debbie|title=Madonna: The Style Book|publisher=[[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]]|year=1999|isbn=0-7119-7511-6}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|ltSpd7Rh_sM|\"Holiday\" (1984 Solid Gold performance)}}\n\n{{Madonna songs}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holiday (Madonna Song)}}\n[[Category:Holiday songs]]\n[[Category:1983 singles]]\n[[Category:1983 songs]]\n[[Category:Madonna (entertainer) songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Sire Records singles]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by John Benitez]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1983 single by Madonna}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name           = Holiday\n| type           = single\n| cover          = Madonna Holiday first UK vinyl cover art Golden Arrow montage.jpg\n| caption        = One of UK edition cover arts\n| alt            = The black-and-white picture of the engine of a train. A symbol of a white arrow is present at the center of the engine's front. The words \"Golden Arrow\" are written on the arrow. A couple walks beside the engine on the platform, the man carrying a suitcase. On the top-right corner of the image, the words \"Madonna\" and \"Holiday\" are written in white, on bright red stripes.\n| artist         = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| album          = [[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna]]\n| border         = yes\n| B-side         = \"I Know It\"<br>\"Think of Me\" <small>(UK)</small>\n| released       = September 7, 1983\n| format         = {{hlist|[[Gramophone record|7-inch]]|[[12-inch single|12-inch]]|[[Compact Disc single|CD]]}}\n| recorded       = February 1983\n| studio         = [[Sigma Sound Studios]]<br><small>([[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]])</small>\n| length         = 6:08\n| label          = {{hlist|[[Sire Records|Sire]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n| genre          = {{hlist|[[Dance-pop]]|[[post-disco]]}}\n| writer         = {{hlist|Curtis Hudson|Lisa Stevens}}\n| producer       = [[John \"Jellybean\" Benitez]]\n| prev_title     = [[Burning Up (Madonna song)|Burning Up]]\n| prev_year      = 1983\n| next_title     = [[Lucky Star (Madonna song)|Lucky Star]]\n| next_year      = 1983\n| misc           =\n}}\n\n\"'''Holiday'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for her eponymous debut [[album]] ''[[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna]]'' (1983). [[Sire Records]] released it as the album's third single on September 7, 1983. \"Holiday\" later appeared remixed on the remix compilation ''[[You Can Dance]]'' (1987) and the greatest hits compilation ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'' (1990), and in its original form on the greatest hits album ''[[Celebration (Madonna album)|Celebration]]'' (2009).\n\nWritten by Curtis Hudson and Lisa Stevens of [[Pure Energy (band)|Pure Energy]], the track was offered to Madonna by her producer [[John \"Jellybean\" Benitez]] when she was looking for a potential hit track to include on her debut album. After accepting the song, she and Benitez worked on it and altered its composition by the addition of a piano solo performed by their friend, [[Fred Zarr]].\n\n\"Holiday\" features instrumentation from guitars, electronic handclaps, a cowbell, and a synthesized string arrangement, while its lyrics speak about the universal sentiment of taking a holiday. Universally acclaimed by [[Music journalism|critics]], the song became Madonna's first mainstream [[hit single]] in the United States, peaking at number 16 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It also became her first top-ten single in several countries, including Australia, Belgium, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom. Madonna has performed \"Holiday\" on most of her tours and it is generally included as a part of the encore. Different performances of the song are included in the recorded releases of her tours. \"Holiday\" has been covered by several artists and appeared in multiple television shows. In 2003, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q Magazine]]'' ranked \"Holiday\" at number 88 in their list of the \"1001 Best Songs Ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muzieklijstjes.nl/Q1001bestsongsever.htm|title=Q - 1001 best songs ever (2003)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background and writing==\nIn 1983, 25-year-old Madonna was recording her eponymous debut album with [[Warner Bros. Records]] producer [[Reggie Lucas]], after [[Sire Records]] green-lit it when her first single \"[[Everybody (Madonna song)|Everybody]]\" became a club hit.<ref>{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=9}}</ref> However, she did not have enough material for the album.<ref name=\"rikky1\">{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=10}}</ref> Lucas brought two new songs to the project and [[John \"Jellybean\" Benitez]], a DJ at Funhouse disco was called to remix the available tracks. In the meantime due to a conflict of interest, Madonna's collaborator on \"Everybody\", [[Stephen Bray]] had sold a song \"Ain't No Big Deal\" to an act called Barracuda on another label, rendering it unavailable for Madonna's album.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/> It was Benitez who discovered a new song written by Curtis Hudson and Lisa Stevens of the pop group [[Pure Energy (band)|Pure Energy]].<ref name=\"cross1\">{{harvnb|Cross|2007|p=26}}</ref> The song, titled \"Holiday\", had been turned down by singers [[Phyllis Hyman]] and [[Mary Wilson (singer)|Mary Wilson]], formerly of [[The Supremes]].<ref name=\"morton1\">{{harvnb|Morton|2002|p=158}}</ref> Hudson and Stevens were asked by Benitez if they had any song for then-unknown Madonna and since their record label [[Prism Records|Prism]] did not want to release \"Holiday\", they gave it to Benitez. Pure Energy recalled in an interview with [[Blogcritics]]:\n<blockquote>\nWe knew that the song had that magic to it. Since we weren't going to be able to record [\"Holiday\"] ourselves, we were really hoping it would fall into the hands of someone who was going to do it justice. Jellybean was shopping it, and I think he pitched it to Phyllis Hyman and a couple of other artists. We didn't pitch the songs that much. I was still hoping we could come around to Pure Energy recording it.<ref name=\"blog\"/>\n</blockquote>\nStevens remembered that she had started playing the beginning chords of \"Holiday\" on a keyboard but could not progress further. Hudson, who felt that the music could lead to something constructive, urged Stevens to experiment with it for a week and ultimately came up with the hook \"Holiday, Celebrate!\", while going back-and-forth between them. Inspired by the opening chords and hearing depressing news on the radio, Hudson started penning down the song and within 30 minutes was able to complete it, with the whole composition and arrangement in his mind. Most of the song was written by him with Stevens suggesting few alterations like the line \"It would be so nice\".<ref name=\"blog\">{{cite web|url=https://blogcritics.org/interview-curtis-hudson-lisa-stevens-songwriters/|title=Interview: Curtis Hudson & Lisa Stevens, Songwriters of Madonna's 'Holiday'|last=Kantor|first=Justin|date=February 1, 2012|accessdate=May 19, 2018|publisher=[[Blogcritics]]}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and composition==\nBenitez and Madonna sent the [[demo (music)|demo]] to their friend, [[Fred Zarr]] so he could change the arrangement and program it differently. After the vocals were added by Madonna, Benitez spent four days and tried to enhance the commercial appeal of the track before the April 1983 deadline set by Madonna's record label.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/><ref name=\"morton1\"/> Benitez had not [[record producer|produced]] any song at that time but was aware of how to reconstruct the different musical pieces in a studio. He composed the sound, assembled the musicians and hummed the tune to them for recording. He also asked Madonna to sing in a \"soulful\" manner on the track.<ref>{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|p=109}}</ref> Just before it was completed, Madonna and Benitez met Zarr at [[Sigma Sound Studios]] in Manhattan where the track was recorded. The singer suggested Zarr to add a piano solo towards the end of the track, as well as asked Hudson to change a part of the funk in the guitar rhythm.<ref name=\"cross1\"/>\n\n{{listen\n | filename     = Madonna-holiday.ogg\n | title        = \"Holiday\"\n | pos          = left\n | description  = A sample of \"Holiday\" featuring its repetitive [[refrain|chorus]] and the four bar sequence in its musical composition\n}}\nPure Energy, who were also present at the recording studio during February 1983,<ref name=\"liner\"/> recalled that the rhythm track was finished in a single day because they did not want to venture further from the demo track. Minor changes were included, like substituting Hudson's [[LinnDrum]] with Zarr's [[Oberheim DMX]]. Other changes were in the vocal delivery from the soul, gospel like singing on the demo to Madonna's \"poppier\" belting; she still remained true to the original melody of the track. The group was not given a production credit on \"Holiday\" since Benitez had presented the track to Sire Records, and he had an existing relationship with Madonna. Although Hudson pressed for a credit, they ultimately let it go since they felt that the song would be their chance to get recognized as efficient songwriters.<ref name=\"blog\"/>\n\nMusically, \"Holiday\" is a [[dance-pop]] and [[post-disco]] song devoid of any particular structure.<ref name=\"Sullivan2013\">{{cite book|first=Steve|last=Sullivan|title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings|year=2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8296-6|pages=336}}</ref> It begins with a chord sequence reminiscent of [[Cyndi Lauper]]'s \"[[Time After Time (Cyndi Lauper song)|Time After Time]]\" (1984).<ref name=\"rikky2\"/> Set in the [[time signature]] of common time with a medium [[tempo]] of 116 [[beats per minute]], the song is composed in the key of [[D major]] and is six minutes seven seconds in length. Madonna's vocal range spans from B<sub>3</sub> to C{{music|sharp}}<sub>5</sub>. The track follows in the [[chord progression]] of G\u2013A\u2013Bm in the first line, when Madonna sings \"Holiday!\" and changes to G\u2013A\u2013F{{music|sharp}}m\u2013G in the second line, when Madonna sings \"Celebrate!\".<ref name=\"sheet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0037594|title=Madonna 'Holiday' Sheet Music|publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Alfred Music Publishing|Alfred Publishing]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|date=November 13, 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe four bar sequence of the progression continues throughout the song and features instrumentation from guitars flicking in the background, electronic handclaps, [[cowbell (instrument)|cowbell]] played by Madonna, and a synthesized string arrangement.<ref name=\"rikky2\"/> A side-by-side repetitive progression is achieved by making use of the [[refrain|chorus]]. Towards the end of the song, a change in the arrangement happens, where a piano [[Break (music)|break]] is heard. Lyrically the song expresses the universal sentiment that everybody needs a holiday from their daily lives.<ref name=\"rikky2\"/> Along with Benitez's production and Zarr's instrumentation, other personnel working on \"Holiday\" included Raymond Hudson on [[bass (sound)|bass]], Bashiri Johnson on [[percussion instrument|percussion]] and Tina B. and Norma Jean Wright who provided background vocals.<ref name=\"liner\">{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna]]|others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|year=1983|type=LP, Vinyl, CD|publisher=[[Sire Records]]|id=9 23867-1}}</ref>\n\n==Release details==\nInitially it was decided that \"[[Lucky Star (Madonna song)|Lucky Star]]\" would be released as a single; instead \"Holiday\" was released in the United States when the latter was picked up by radios for airplay and became a dance hit.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/> Warner Bros. Records were not prepared for the song to take off like that and hence no music video was released for it.<ref name=\"blog\"/> The original British cover art for \"Holiday\" did not carry Madonna's picture since Sire did not want the British people to find out that she was not a R&B artist. Instead it carried the picture of a train station and an engine.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/> \"Holiday\" was later remixed in [[Dub music|dub]] and [[Groove (music)|groove]] versions for the 1987 remix album ''[[You Can Dance]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r12207|pure_url=yes}}|title= You Can Dance > Overview|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=August 4, 1987|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> It also appeared in her first greatest hits compilation, ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'', in a remixed and shortened form.<ref>{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=11}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Holiday\" has been released three times as a single: in January 1984, reaching number six; reissued in August 1985, reaching number 2 (only being kept from number one by her own \"[[Into the Groove]]\" single); and re-released with new artwork in 1991 to promote ''The Immaculate Collection'' with a limited edition EP titled ''[[The Immaculate Collection#The Holiday Collection|The Holiday Collection]]'', which contained tracks omitted from the compilation; this version reached number five. Although the song was released to promote the greatest hits collection, it did not include the shorter remix from the album, instead it included the original album version from ''Madonna'' (1983).<ref name=\"uk\"/> The photography used for the 1991 release was by [[Steven Meisel]] and had previously been used for the February 1991 cover for ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' Italia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.it/en/people-are-talking-about/obsession-of-the-day/2011/12/madonna-superbowl-meisel|title=Madonna Come Marilyn|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] Italia|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\nIt has been featured in [[Wii]] dance video game ''[[Just Dance 2]]'' .\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Madonna 5 (24527521109) (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Madonna performing \"Holiday\" as the encore of the [[Rebel Heart Tour]] in 2015|alt=Madonna in a red hat and blue jacket with a red-and-blue flag wrapped around her performing onstage]]\nAuthor Rikky Rooksby in his book ''The Complete Guide to the Music of Madonna'' commented that \"'Holiday' was as infectious as the plague. One listen and you could not get the damn [[Hook (music)|hook]] out of your mind.\" He also likened the track as getting on a [[carousel]] and enjoying the ride, or get really bothered by the song going \"on-and-on\" for six minutes.<ref name=\"rikky2\">{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=13}}</ref> Jim Farber of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' commented that \"Holiday\" satisfied the musical ear of both the sides of the Atlantic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,255548,00.html|title=The Girl Material|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=July 27, 2001|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> While reviewing ''[[The Immaculate Collection]]'' album, [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] from ''Entertainment Weekly'' commented that \"Holiday\" was a \"spunky dance-beat trifle\". He also complimented the song's expert production.<ref>{{cite web|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|title=Madonna: The Immaculate Collection|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318856,00.html|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=December 14, 1990|accessdate=March 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\nMary Cross in her biography of Madonna, described \"Holiday\" as \"a simple song with a fresh appeal and a good mood.\"<ref name=\"cross2\">{{harvnb|Cross|2007|p=27}}</ref> According to author [[Lucy O'Brien]], who wrote in the biography ''[[Madonna: Like an Icon]]'', the track was an example of Madonna's early musical endeavors being about the \"power of dance\". She believed that the song cemented her style of music with its \"bubbling Latin undertow, crunchy bass and strings and Fred Zarr's elegant closing piano riff\". O'Brien declared \"Holiday\" as Madonna's \"most\" persuasive dance song with its \"tension, release, resolution and celebratory\" nature enhanced by Madonna's \"playful commands and exhortations\".<ref>{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|pp=106\u2013107}}</ref> Sal Cinquemani of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' described the song as airy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-madonna-remaster|title=Madonna (Remastered): Review|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=September 9, 2001|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] from [[AllMusic]] called it effervescent and one of the great songs of the ''Madonna'' album.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r12203|pure_url=yes}}|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|title= Madonna > Overview|date=June 10, 1983|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> While reviewing ''The Immaculate Collection'', he called it one of her greatest hits.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r12210|pure_url=yes}}|title= The Immaculate Collection > Overview|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=December 12, 1990|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> Don Shewey of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' commented that the simple lyrics of the song sound clever.<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/reviews/album/3045/21667|title=Madonna: Madonna album review|last=Shewey|first=Don|date=September 25, 1983|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n[[File:HolidayRIT (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Madonna performing \"Holiday\" on the [[Re-Invention World Tour]] (2004)]]\n\"Holiday\" was released on September 7, 1983, and became Madonna's first hit single in the United States and remained on the charts from Thanksgiving to Christmas 1983.<ref name=\"morton1\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Grein|first=Paul|title=Chart Beat|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ziQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT5&dq=Madonna+Holiday+single+release+September+1983|date=February 2, 1985|accessdate=March 10, 2013|journal=Billboard|page=6|issn=0006-2510|volume=97|issue=5}}</ref> It was Madonna's first song to enter the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], at 88 on the issue dated October 29, 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1983-10-29/hot-100?order=gainer|title=The Billboard Hot 100: Week Ending October 29, 1983|date=October 29, 1983|accessdate=July 3, 2009|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> and reached a peak of 16 on January 28, 1984 and was on the chart for 21 weeks.<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1984-01-28/hot-100?order=timeon|title=The Billboard Hot 100: Week Ending January 28, 1984|date=January 28, 1984|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 26, 2011}}</ref> The song debuted at eight on the [[Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart on the issue dated November 2, 1983 and was Madonna's first number one single on the Hot Dance Club Play chart remaining at the top for five weeks.<ref name=\"rikky1\"/><ref name=\"amgbb\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=madonna-r12203/charts-awards/billboard-single|pure_url=yes}}|title= Madonna > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles |publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> The song also made an entry in the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart and peaked at 25, remaining on the chart for 20 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/r-b-hip-hop-songs?chartDate=1983-11-17&order=timeon|title=''Billboard'' Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs: Week Ending November 19, 1983|date=November 19, 1983|work=Billboard|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> In Canada, the song debuted at number 48 position of the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' singles chart on January 21, 1984<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4430&volume=39&issue=20&issue_dt=January%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 4430|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022014719/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4430&volume=39&issue=20&issue_dt=January%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and peaked at number 39.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8308&volume=39&issue=25&issue_dt=February%2025%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 8308|work=RPM|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022014558/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8308&volume=39&issue=25&issue_dt=February%2025%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The song again entered the chart at number 45 in March 1984,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6277&volume=40&issue=2&issue_dt=March%2017%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 6277|work=RPM|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022015344/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6277&volume=40&issue=2&issue_dt=March%2017%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 22, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and peaked at number 32 on April 1984.<ref name=\"can\"/> It was present on the chart for a total of 12 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6703&volume=40&issue=7&issue_dt=April%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 6703|work=RPM|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=July 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010154742/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6703&volume=40&issue=7&issue_dt=April%2021%201984&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archivedate=October 10, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Holiday\" was released in 1984 whence it charted and reached a peak of six on the chart. However, a rerelease in 1985 with \"Think of Me\" on the B-side, saw the song enter the charts at number&nbsp;32 and reached a new peak of two on the chart, being held off the number one spot by Madonna's own \"[[Into the Groove]]\", while being present for ten weeks. Another re-release in 1991 saw the song reach a peak of five on the chart.<ref name=\"uk\"/> The song was certified gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) in August 1985,<ref name=\"bpi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|title=BPI \u2013 Certified Awards Search|date=August 1, 1983|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=August 27, 2009}}</ref> and according to the [[Official Charts Company]], \"Holiday\" has sold 718,000 copies there as of August 2017.<ref name=\"uksales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/madonna-s-official-top-40-biggest-selling-singles__8266/|title=Open your chart to me... Madonna's Official Top 40 Biggest Selling Singles|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=August 16, 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> Across Europe, the song reached the top ten of Belgium, Netherlands, Germany and Ireland<ref name=\"bel\"/><ref name=\"dutch\"/><ref name=\"german\"/><ref name=\"irish\"/> while reaching the top 40 in France, Sweden and Switzerland.<ref name=\"france\"/><ref name=\"sweden\"/><ref name=\"swiss\"/> According to ''[[Music & Media]]'' magazine the song had sold around 1.5&nbsp;million copies in Europe by September 1985.<ref name=\"eurosales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Music-Media-IDX/IDX/80s/85/M&M-1985-09-23-OCR-Page-0008.pdf|title=Madonna Mania Now Spreading All Over Europe|date=September 23, 1985|accessdate=June 10, 2018|work=[[Music & Media]]}}</ref> \"Holiday\" reached top five on the [[Kent Music Report]] chart of Australia.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> The song debuted at number 37 on the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]], making it Madonna's debut chart appearance in the country. It peaked at number seven.<ref name=\"sweden\"/>\n\nDuring a 2005 interview with Harry Smith of [[CBS News]], Madonna singled out \"Holiday\" as a favorite amongst her top-ten charting singles, though Smith corrected that it had peaked at a much lower position.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/12/13/earlyshow/leisure/celebspot/main1121578.shtml|title=Madonna, Elvis Alike In Key Way|last=Dakss|first=Brian|date=December 13, 2005|accessdate=July 3, 2009|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> Pure Energy remembered that the success of \"Holiday\" also helped them financially, the royalties helping them move out of the [[boarding house]] they had been living. Hudson confirmed that the song still generated money for them, saying that \"Can you live off of one hit? Yes, you can if you get the right hit. It can last you a lifetime. We've been living proof of that\". However, the band were not able to replicate their songwriting success of \"Holiday\" with later releases, since the music business still expected them to concoct something like the track.<ref name=\"blog\"/>\n\n==Live performances==\nMadonna has performed \"Holiday\" on almost all of her tours, namely [[The Virgin Tour]], [[Who's That Girl World Tour|Who's That Girl]], [[Blond Ambition World Tour|Blond Ambition]], [[The Girlie Show World Tour|The Girlie Show]], [[Drowned World Tour|Drowned World]], [[Re-Invention World Tour|Re-Invention]], [[Sticky & Sweet Tour]] and [[Rebel Heart Tour]]. In 1984, Madonna performed Holiday on the hit dance show ''[[American Bandstand]]'' with [[Dick Clark]].<ref name=\"cross2\"/> Madonna then added it to the set list of her 1985 Virgin Tour. It was performed as the second song of the tour.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=42}}</ref> The same year she performed the song at the [[Live Aid]] benefit concert in Philadelphia in July.<ref name=\"voller1\">{{harvnb|Voller|1999|p=56}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HolidayUnderGround2 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Madonna performing \"Holiday\" on the [[Blond Ambition World Tour]] in 1990|alt=Madonna in a polka dotted blouse and white pants singing onstage]]\nThe Who's That Girl World Tour in 1987 had Madonna performing \"Holiday\" as the last song of the tour. Madonna performed an energetic version of the song, signalling the celebratory and wholesome nature of the song's theme.<ref>{{harvnb|Kellner|1995|p=276}}</ref> She sang the final chorus twice, and on some dates asked the audience for a comb so that she could fix her hair and finished the performance.<ref name=\"ciao\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[Ciao Italia: Live from Italy]]|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1988}}</ref> Two different performances are found in ''[[Ciao Italia: Live from Italy]]'' tour video filmed at [[Stadio Olimpico di Torino|Stadio Communale]] in [[Turin]], Italy on September 4, 1987<ref name=\"ciao\"/> and the ''Who's That Girl: Live in Japan'' tour video filmed at [[Korakuen Stadium]] in [[Tokyo]], Japan on June 22, 1987.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Who's That Girl&nbsp;\u2013 Live in Japan|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1987}}</ref>\n\nFor the Blond Ambition World Tour in 1990, Madonna said, \"I wanted to throw an old song for fun, and 'Holiday' seemed to be a universal favourite. In addition to that it's one of the only old songs I've done that I can still sing and not feel I've totally outgrown it.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Michael|2004|p=52}}</ref> Performing it as a part of the encore, Madonna appeared on the stage in a polka-dotted blouse with matching flounces at the bottom of white trousers and hair in a top knot with a ponytail.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=84}}</ref> The costume was adopted from a ''[[My Fair Lady (film)|My Fair Lady]]'' dress and was designed by [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]]. Three different performances are found in the ''Blond Ambition: Japan Tour 90'' VHS, the ''[[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]'' VHS and the ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare|Truth or Dare]]'' documentary. The performance included in the documentary was used as a music video to promote it.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=Blond Ambition: Japan Tour 90|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[Blond Ambition World Tour Live]]|type=VHS|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1990}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Truth or Dare|last=Goodlum|first=Jeff|date=December 4, 2000|journal=Rolling Stone|volume=1079|issue=19|issn=0035-791X}}</ref> The performance received four nominations at the [[1992 MTV Video Music Awards]], including Best Female Video, Best Dance Video, Best Choreography in Video and Best Cinematography in Video, but did not win any of the categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1992/|title=MTV Video Music Awards&nbsp;\u2013 1992&nbsp;\u2013 Highlights, Winners, Performers|publisher=[[MTV]]|accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn The Girlie Show in 1993, the song was performed in an alternate version as the second-to-last song of the tour.<ref name=\"gs\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[The Girlie Show: Live Down Under]]|type=DVD|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=1993}}</ref> It had a military theme to it.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=139}}</ref> Halfway through the performance Madonna paused the song for a military drill with the dancers and the audience.<ref name=\"lull\">{{harvnb|Lull|Hinerman|1997|p=250}}</ref> The performance met with strong reaction in Puerto Rico, when Madonna rubbed the Puerto Rican national flag between her legs in between the performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3704915.stm|title=Show-stealer Madonna on tour|last=Smith|first=Neil|date=May 24, 2004|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref> For the Drowned World Tour in 2001 Madonna wore a fur coat, velvet fedora and a customised [[Dolce & Gabbana]] T-shirt which proclaimed 'Mother' in the front and 'F*cker' in the back painted in silver. This demonstrated her ghetto-girl appearance adopted for the song's performance.<ref>{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=174}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sticky-holiday-MJ-tribute.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Michael Jackson]] tribute during \"Holiday\" on the [[Sticky & Sweet Tour]] shows in 2009]]\nIn the Re-Invention Tour in 2004, the song was again performed as the ending song of the tour.<ref name=tim>{{harvnb|Timmerman|2007|p=47}}</ref> The song was given a tribal feeling with Madonna wearing Scottish kilts during the performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,640170,00.html|title=Madonna's Wardrobe Ready for Reinvention|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=April 3, 2004|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> The performance started with Madonna and her dancers doing a dance routine in front of the stage, then Madonna going on the revolving tiers of the stage to sing the song as confetti fell from above.<ref name=tim/> The performance was included in the ''[[I'm Going to Tell You a Secret]]'' live album and documentary.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[I'm Going to Tell You a Secret]]|type=DVD|publisher=Warner Home Video|year=2005}}</ref> Stephen Thomas Erlewine of Allmusic commented that the performance \"feels like they could fit the Eurotrash, campy retro-disco feel of [[Confessions Tour|Confessions]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r834380|pure_url=yes}}|title=I'm Going to Tell You a Secret > Overview |last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=September 9, 2006|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe song was added to the 2009 leg of her Sticky & Sweet Tour. It replaced the song \"Heartbeat\" from ''[[Hard Candy (Madonna album)|Hard Candy]]'' and was used as a tribute to singer [[Michael Jackson]] who died a week prior to the start of the second leg of the tour.<ref name=\"Madonna's Michael Jackson Tribute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Madonnas_Emotional_Onstage_Tribute_to_Jackson/5664629|title=Madonna's Emotional Onstage Tribute to Jackson|publisher=Hollywood.com|accessdate=July 5, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706064807/http://www.hollywood.com/news/Madonnas_Emotional_Onstage_Tribute_to_Jackson/5664629|archivedate=July 6, 2009|date=July 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"sticky\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-07-06/entertainment/0907060107_1_michael-jackson-impersonator-madonna|title=Madonna pays tribute to Michael Jackson in concert|last=Saad|first=Nardeen|date=July 5, 2009|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref> As Madonna sang the song, a picture of a young Jackson appeared on stage, followed by a Jackson impersonator wearing garments in Jackson style.<ref name=\"sticky\"/> The music then switched to a medley of his songs, like \"[[Billie Jean]]\" and \"[[Wanna Be Startin' Somethin']]\", and the impersonator worked through his moves, including the [[Moonwalk (dance)|moonwalk]] as well as the spinning and gyrating.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1615279/20090705/madonna.jhtml|title=Madonna Salutes Michael Jackson At London's O2 Arena|last=Rodriquez|first=Jason|date=July 5, 2009|accessdate=July 6, 2009|publisher=MTV News}}</ref> Madonna clapped her hands, swayed from side to side and jumped up and down while images of Jackson over the years flashed on a big screen.<ref name=\"mtv\"/> After the performance, Madonna told the crowd, \"Let's give it up for one of the greatest artists the world has ever known,\" and the crowd applauded.<ref name=\"sticky\"/>\n\nIn 2012, Madonna performed \"Holiday\" on some shows of [[The MDNA Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ganz|first=Caryn|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/09/madonna-mdna-tour-yankee-stadium-review/|title=Act of God: Madonna's MDNA Tour Comes to Yankee Stadium|date=September 10, 2012|accessdate=April 15, 2019|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]}}</ref> The song was the closing number to Madonna's [[Rebel Heart Tour]] in 2015\u20132016, it included an excerpt from [[Bob James (musician)|Bob James]]' cover of \"[[Take Me to the Mardi Gras]]\".<ref name=\"videorebel\"/> She performed the song while she's wrapped with the country's flag. She exits from stage while she's levitated by a harness and rope.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2015/09/rebel-heart-tour-madonna-takes-the-verizon-center-by-storm-review/|title=Madonna Takes The Verizon Center by Storm: Review|date=September 9, 2015|accessdate=September 17, 2017|work=Metro Weekly}}</ref> The performance was included in the live album ''[[Rebel Heart Tour (album)|Rebel Heart Tour]]'' recorded in Sydney, Australia, and released in September 2017.<ref name=\"videorebel\">{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[Rebel Heart Tour (album)|Rebel Heart Tour]]|medium=2\u00d7 CD, DVD, Blu-ray|publisher=Eagle Records|year=2017}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Covers and media appearance==\n{{See also|List of cover versions of Madonna songs|List of Madonna tribute albums}}\n\nBritish [[synthpop]] band [[Heaven 17]] recorded a cover for the 1999 compilation ''Virgin Voices Vol. 1: A Tribute To Madonna''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4467|pure_url=yes}}|title=Heaven 17 > Overview |last=Ankeny|first=Jason|date=October 28, 1999|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> In 2002, Mad'House recorded a [[Electronic dance music|Club]] cover of the song for their album ''Absolutely Mad''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r606622|pure_url=yes}}|title=Absolutely Mad > Overview|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=August 9, 2009}}</ref> [[Girl Authority]] covered the song in 2007 for their album, ''[[Road Trip (Girl Authority album)|Road Trip]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmv.com.hk/product/rockpop.asp?sku=720230|title=Girl Authority&nbsp;\u2013 Roadtrip|publisher=[[HMV Group]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924031157/http://www.hmv.com.hk/product/rockpop.asp?sku=720230|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1986, Dutch rap duo [[MC Miker G & DJ Sven]] released \"[[Holiday Rap]]\", a song which sampled the tune and chorus of Madonna's \"Holiday\". It achieved commercial success by peaking the charts in countries like France, Netherlands and Switzerland and going the top ten of Austria, Norway, Britain and Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/en/showitem.asp?interpret=M%2EC%2E+Miker+%27G%27+%26+Deejay+Sven&titel=Holiday+Rap&cat=s|title=M.C. Miker and Deejay Sven&nbsp;\u2013 Holiday Rap (Song)|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> The bassline of the song was [[sampling (music)|sampled]] by [[The Avalanches]] for their 2000 album ''[[Since I Left You]]''. It was used on the songs \"Stay Another Season\" and \"Little Journey\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/a/avalanches-since.shtml|title=The Avalanches: Since I Left You < Reviews|last=Hseigh|first=Christine|date=November 6, 2001|work=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe song was redone by the ''[[Will & Grace]]'' cast as \"He's Hot\" for the sitcom's soundtrack in 2004 and even includes vocal samples from Madonna herself. Almost all of the instrumental part of the song \"He's Hot!\" uses samples from the original song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12178639|title='Will & Grace' Compilation Album in Works|last=Hay|first=Carla|date=July 17, 2004|publisher=Yahoo! Music Canada|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> The Canadian teen drama ''[[Degrassi: The Next Generation]]'', which is known for naming each episode after an 80s hit song, named a two-part episode after \"Holiday\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/degrassi-the-next-generation/holiday-1/episode/278919/summary.html|title=Degrassi: The Next Generation: Holiday (1)|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/degrassi-the-next-generation/holiday-2/episode/278921/summary.html|title=Degrassi: The Next Generation: Holiday (2)|publisher=TV.com|accessdate=July 8, 2009}}</ref> In 2006, critics noted strong similarity between \"Holiday\" and American singer [[Jessica Simpson]]'s single \"[[A Public Affair (song)|A Public Affair]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/25/AR2006082500226.html|title=Two Divas: One Has No Shame (Or Talent)|first=Allison|last=Stewart|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 27, 2006|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/1092655881.html?dids=1092655881:1092655881&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+10%2C+2006&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=They%27re+baaa-aaack&pqatl=google|title=They're baaa-aaack|work=Chicago Tribune|date=August 10, 2006|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> When criticized for its unoriginality, Simpson told [[MTV]]: \"I think people are ready to hear something that Madonna used to do. We all need to hear that every now and again. It wasn't a sample or something I meant to do, but she did influence me and still does today.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1537645/jessica-covers-song-that-helped-her-let-nick-go.jhtml|title=Jessica Simpson Covers Song That Convinced Her To Let Nick Go|first=Corey|last=Moss|publisher=MTV News|date=August 2, 2006|accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref> In 2008, \"Holiday\" appeared on the video game ''[[Karaoke Revolution]] Presents: American Idol Encore''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.cube.ign.com/articles/666/666541p1.html|title=Karaoke Revolution Party: Good times never seemed so good.|last=Miller|first=Jonathan|date=November 15, 2005|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=July 8, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930073707/http://uk.cube.ign.com/articles/666/666541p1.html|archivedate=September 30, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Kelis]] often performs a [[Mashup (music)|mashup]] of her own hit \"[[Milkshake (song)|Milkshake]]\" with \"Holiday\" live. In 2003, a snippet of the song appeared in the film ''[[Rugrats Go Wild]]'', when the families went on their [[cruise ship|cruise]].<ref>{{cite AV media|year=2003|title=Rugrats Go Wild|accessdate=February 23, 2013|type=DVD|time=|publisher=[[Nickelodeon Movies]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom Inc]]}}</ref>\n\n==