tegory:1965 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: the USA \u2192 the US, \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Ski_Team"}
{"title_page": "Mohicans", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Mohican}}\n{{distinguish|text=the [[Mohegan]]s, a different Algonquian-speaking tribe living in eastern (upper Thames valley) Connecticut}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group         = Mohicans<br/><small>{{lang|mjy|Muhhekunneuw}}</small>\n|image         = File:Mohican distribution map.svg\n|image_caption = Historic territory of the Mohicans\n|pop           = {{circa}} 3,000\n|popplace      = {{USA}} ([[Shawano County, Wisconsin]])\n|langs         = [[English language|English]] (originally [[Mohican language|Mohican]])\n|rels          = [[Moravian Church]]\n|related       = [[Lenape]], [[Mohegan]], [[Pequot]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Mohicans''' ({{IPAc-en|m|o\u028a|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|k|\u0259n|s}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|k|\u0259n|s}}, alternate spelling: Mahican) are an [[Eastern Algonquian]] [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[Native Americans in the United States|tribe]] that was Algonquian-speaking. As part of the Eastern Algonquian family of tribes, they are related to the abutting [[Lenape]], who occupied territory to the south as far as the Atlantic coast. The Mohicans occupied the upper tidal [[Hudson River Valley]], including the confluence of the Mohawk River (where present-day [[Albany, New York]], developed) and into western New England centered on the upper Housatonic watershed. After 1680, due to conflicts with the [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]] during the [[Beaver Wars]], many were driven southeastward across the present-day Massachusetts western border and the [[Taconic Mountains]] to [[Berkshire County]] around [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]].\n \nSince the forcible relocation of American Indian populations to reservations in the [[American Frontier|American West]] during the 1830s, most descendants of the Mohicans are located in [[Shawano County, Wisconsin]].  Decades later they eventually formed the federally recognized [[Stockbridge-Munsee Community]] with registered members of the [[Munsee]] people and have a {{convert|22000|acre|km2|adj=on|0}} reservation.\n\nFollowing the disruption of the [[American Revolutionary War]], most of the Mohican descendants first migrated westward to join the [[Iroquois]] [[Oneida people|Oneida]] on their reservation in central New York. The Oneida gave them about 22,000 acres for their use. After more than two decades, in the 1820s and 1830s, the Oneida and the Stockbridge moved again, pressured to relocate to northeastern [[Wisconsin]] under the federal [[Indian Removal]] program.<ref name=EBmohs>[http://p2.www.britannica.com/ebc/article-9370993 EB-Mohicans \"Mohican\" (history)], ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', 2007 {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20070624083706/http://p2.www.britannica.com/ebc/article-9370993 |date=24 June 2007 }}</ref> A group of Mohicans also migrated to Canada to live with Iroquois Six Nations.\n\nThe tribe identified by the place where they lived: {{lang|mjy|Muh-he-ka-neew}} (or \"people of the continually flowing waters\").<ref>''Stockbridge, Past and Present''; Electa Jones</ref> The word {{lang|mjy|Muh-he-kan}} refers to a great sea or body of water, and the Hudson River reminded them of their place of origin, so they named the Hudson River {{lang|mjy|Mahicanituck}}, or the river where there are people from the continually flowing waters.<ref>\"Mohican Oral Tribal History as recorded by Hendrick Aupaumut\" and printed in ''Stockbridge, Past and Present'' by Electa Jones.</ref> Therefore, they, along with other tribes living along the Hudson River (such as the ''[[Munsee]]'', known by the dialect of Lenape that they spoke, and ''[[Wappinger]]''), were called \"the River Indians\" by the Dutch and English. The Dutch heard and wrote the term for the people of the area variously as: ''Mahigan'', ''Mahikander'', ''Mahinganak'', ''Maikan'' and ''Mawhickon'', among other variants, which the English simplified later to ''Mohican'' or ''Mahican'', in a transliteration to their spelling system. The French, adopting names used by their Indian allies in Canada, knew the Mohicans as the {{lang|fr|Loups}} (or wolves); similarly, they referred to the [[Iroquois]] as the \"Snake People\" (or \"Five Nations\").  Like the Munsee and Wappinger peoples, the Mohicans were related to the [[Lenape people]], who occupied coastal areas from western Long Island to the [[Delaware River]] valley to the south.\n\nIn the late twentieth century, the Mohicans joined other former New York tribes and the Oneida in filing land claims against New York state for what were considered unconstitutional purchases after the Revolutionary War. In 2010, outgoing governor [[David Paterson]] announced a land exchange with the Stockbridge-Munsee that would enable them to build a large casino on {{convert|330|acre}} in [[Sullivan County, New York|Sullivan County]] in the [[Catskills]], in exchange for dropping their larger claim in [[Madison County, New York|Madison County]]. The deal had many opponents.\n\n==Territory==\nThe Mohicans were living in and around the [[Hudson River]] (or {{lang|mjy|Mahicannituck}}) at the time of their first contact with [[Europe]]ans traders along the river in the 1590s. After 1609 at the time of the Dutch settlement of [[New Netherland]], they also ranged along the eastern [[Mohawk River]] and the [[Hoosic River]]. Most of their communities lay along the upper tidal reaches of the Hudson River and along the watersheds of Kinderhook-Claverack-Taghkanic Creek, the Roeliff Jansen Kill, Catskil Creek, and adjacent areas of the Housatonic Watershed. Mohican territory reached along Hudson River watersheds northeastward to Wood Creek just south of [[Lake Champlain]]. In [[Mohican language|their own language]], the Mohicans identified collectively as the {{lang|mjy|Muhhekunneuw}}, \"people of the great tidal river\".<ref name=sultzman>[http://www.dickshovel.com/Mahican.html Sultzman, Lee. \"Mahican History\"]</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nMohican villages were fairly large. Usually consisting of 20 to 30 mid-sized [[longhouse]]s, they were located on hills and heavily fortified. Their large cornfields were located nearby. Agriculture and gathering of nuts, fruits and roots provided most of their diet, but was supplemented by the men hunting game, and fishing. Mohican villages were governed by hereditary [[sachem]]s advised by a council of clan elders. A general council of sachems met regularly at [[Schodack, New York|Shodac]] (east of present-day Albany) to decide important matters affecting the entire confederacy.<ref name=sultzman/> In his history of the Indians of the Hudson River, [[Edward Manning Ruttenber]] described the clans of the Mohicans as the Bear, the Turkey, the Turtle, and the Wolf, with the Wolf serving as a defensive shield in the north against the Mohawk.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nLike their Munsee-speaking relatives to the south, Mohican villages followed a dispersed settlement pattern, with each community likely dominated by a single lineage or clan. Usually consisting of a small cluster of small and mid-sized [[longhouse]]s, they were located along floodplains. During times of war, they built fortifications in defensive locations (such as along ridges) as places of retreat. Their cornfields were located near to their communities; varieties of squash, beans, sunflowers, and other crops from the [[Eastern Agricultural Complex]]. Horticulture and gathering of nuts (hickory, butternuts, black walnuts and acorns), fruits (blueberries, raspberries, juneberries among many others) and roots (groundnuts, wood lilies, arrowroot among others) provided much of their diet. This was supplemented by the men hunting game (turkeys, deer, elk, bears, and moose in the Taconics) and fishing (sturgeon, alewives, shad, eels, lamprey and striped bass). Mohican communities were governed by hereditary [[sachem]]s advised by a council of clan elders. A general council of sachems met regularly at [[Schodack, New York|Schodac]] (east of present-day Albany) to decide important matters affecting the entire group.<ref name=sultzman/> Moravian missionary [[John Heckewelder]] and early anthropologist [[Lewis H. Morgan]] both learned, from Mohican informants, that their matrilineal society was divided into three phratries (Turkey, Turtle and Wolf) and these divided into clans or subclans, including a potentially prominent Bear Clan. This is supported by Mohican signatures on treaties and land deeds (see the works of [[Shirley Dunn]]).\n\n==History==\n===Mohican Confederacy===\nThe Mohicans were a confederacy of five tribes and as many as forty villages.<ref name=sultzman/>\n* ''Mohican proper'', lived in the vicinity of today's [[Albany, New York|Albany]] ({{lang|mjy|Pempotowwuthut-Muhhcanneuw}}, \"the fireplace of the Mahican Nation\") west towards the Mohawk River and to the northwest to Lake Champlain and Lake George\n* {{lang|mjy|Mechkentowoon}}, lived along the west shore of the Hudson River above the Catskill Creek)\n* {{lang|mjy|Wawyachtonoc}} (or {{lang|mjy|Wawayachtonoc}},  \"eddy people\" or \"people of the curving channel\"), lived in [[Dutchess County, New York|Dutchess County]] and [[Columbia County, New York|Columbia County]] eastward to the Housatonic River in [[Litchfield County, Connecticut|Litchfield County]], Connecticut, main village was ''Weantinock'', additional villages: ''Shecomeco'', ''Wechquadnach'', ''Pamperaug'', ''Bantam'', ''Weataug'', ''Scaticook'')\n* ''Westenhuck'' (from {{lang|mjy|hous atenuc}}, \"on the other side of the mountains\"), the name of a village near [[Great Barrington, Massachusetts|Great Barrington]], Massachusetts. Often called the \"[[Housatonic Valley|Housatonic people]],\" they lived in the [[Housatonic Valley]] in Connecticut and Massachusetts and in the vicinity of Great Barrington, which they called {{lang|mjy|Mahaiwe}}, meaning \"the place downstream\"<ref>Donald B. Ricky: ''Indians of Maryland Past and Present'', Verlag: Somerset Pubs, 1999; {{ISBN|978-0403098774}}</ref>\n* ''Wiekagjoc'' (from {{lang|mjy|wikwajek}}, \"upper reaches of a river\"), lived east of the Hudson Rivers near the city of [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]], Columbia County, New York<ref>Allen W. Trelease, William A. Starna: ''Indian Affairs in Colonial New York Indian Affairs in Colonial New York:'' The Seventeenth Century the Seventeenth Century, Seite 8, University of Nebraska Press; 1997, {{ISBN|978-0803294318}}</ref>\n\n=== Conflict with the Mohawk ===\n[[File:Land deed, May 31, 1664, Willem Hoffmeyer purchase of 3 islands in the Hudson River near Troy from three native Mahicans - Albany Institute of History and Art - DSC07971.JPG|thumb|Land deed, 31 May 1664, Willem Hoffmeyer purchase of 3 islands in the Hudson River near Troy from three native Mohicans \u2013 Albany Institute of History and Art]]\n\nThe Algonquians (Mohican) and Iroquois (Mohawk) were traditional competitors and enemies. Iroquois oral tradition, as recorded in the ''[[Jesuit Relations]]'', speaks of a war between the Mohawks and an alliance of the Susquehannock and [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] (sometime between 1580 and 1600). This was perhaps in response to the formation of the League of the Iroquois.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/americanheritage00bran Brandon, William. ''American Heritage Book of Indians'', (Alvin M. Josephy, ed.), American Heritage Pub. Co. 1961, p. 187]</ref>\n\nIn September 1609 Henry Hudson encountered Mohican villages just below present day Albany, with whom he traded goods for furs. Hudson returned to Holland with a cargo of valuable furs which immediately attracted Dutch merchants to the area. The first Dutch fur traders arrived on the Hudson River the following year to trade with the Mohicans. Besides exposing them to European epidemics, the fur trade destabilized the region.<ref name=sultzman/>\n\nIn 1614, the Dutch decided to establish a permanent trading post on [[Castle Island (New York)|Castle Island]], on the site of a previous French post that had been long abandoned; but first they had to arrange a truce to end fighting which had broken out between the Mohicans and Mohawks. Fighting broke out again between the Mohicans and Mohawks in 1617, and with [[Fort Nassau (North River)|Fort Nassau]] badly damaged by a freshet, the Dutch abandoned the fort. In 1618, having once again negotiated a truce, the Dutch rebuilt Fort Nassau on higher ground.<ref>[http://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsAmericas/NorthMohicans.htm \"Mahican Confederacy\", The History Files]</ref> Late that year, Fort Nassau was destroyed by flooding and abandoned for good. In 1624, Captain [[Cornelius Jacobsen May]] sailed the {{lang|nl|Nieuw Nederlandt}} upriver and landed eighteen families of [[Walloons]] on a plain opposite Castle Island. They commenced to construct [[Fort Orange (New Netherland)|Fort Orange]].\n\nThe Mohicans invited the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] and [[Innu|Montagnais]] to bring their furs to Fort Orange as an alternate to French traders in Quebec. Seeing the Mohicans extended their control over the fur trade, the Mohawk attacked, with initial success. In 1625 or 1626 the Mohicans destroyed the easternmost Iroquois \"castle\". The Mohawks then re-located south of the [[Mohawk River]], closer to Fort Orange. In July 1626 many of the settlers moved to [[New Amsterdam]] because of the conflict. The Mohicans requested help from the Dutch and Commander Daniel Van Krieckebeek set out from the fort with six soldiers. Van Krieckebeek, three soldiers, and twenty-four Mohicans were killed when their party was ambushed by the Mohawk about mile from the fort. The Mohawks withdrew with some body parts of those slain for later consumption as a demonstration of supremacy.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qJ-KAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA115 Parmenter, Jon W., \"Separate Vessels\", ''The Worlds of the Seventeenth-Century Hudson Valley''], (Jaap Jacobs, L. H. Roper, eds.) SUNY Press, 2014,  {{ISBN|9781438450971}} p. 113</ref>\n\nWar continued to rage between the Mohicans and Mohawks throughout the area from Skahn\u00e9htati ([[Schenectady, New York|Schenectady]]) to Kinderhoek [[Kinderhook (village), New York|Kinderhook]].<ref name=Chronicle>[https://books.google.com/books?id=XNU0AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=albany+chronicles&q=orange Reynolds, Cuyler. ''Albany Chronicles: A History of the City Arranged Chronologically'', J.B. Lyon Company, 1906]{{PD-notice}}</ref> By 1629, the Mohawks had taken over territories on the west bank of the Hudson River that were formerly held by the Mohicans.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Mohawk_Frontier.html?id=xWsq2NPeYRcC Burke Jr, T. E., & Starna, W. A. (1991). ''Mohawk Frontier: The Dutch Community of Schenectady, New York, 1661\u20131710''], SUNY Press. p. 26</ref> The conflict caused most of the Mohican to migrate eastward across the [[Hudson River]] into western Massachusetts and Connecticut.  The Mohawks gained a near-monopoly in the fur trade with the Dutch by prohibiting the nearby Algonquian-speaking tribes to the north or east to trade.\n\n===Stockbridge===\nMany Mohicans settled in the town of [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], where they gradually became known as the \"Stockbridge Indians\". {{lang|mjy|Etow Oh Koam}}, one of their chiefs, accompanied three Mohawk chiefs on a state visit to [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] and her government in England in 1710. They were popularly referred to as the [[Four Mohawk Kings]].\n\n[[File:Mohawk king engraving.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Mohican chief {{lang|mjy|Etow Oh Koam}}, referred to as one of the [[Four Mohawk Kings]] in a state visit to [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] in 1710. By [[John Simon (engraver)|John Simon]], c. 1750.]]\nThe Stockbridge Indians allowed [[Protestant]] [[missionary|missionaries]], including [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Jonathan Edwards]], to live among them.  In the 18th century, many converted to [[Christianity]], while keeping certain traditions of their own.  They fought on the side of the British colonists in the [[French and Indian War]] (also known as the [[Seven Years' War]]).  During the [[American Revolution]], they sided with the colonists.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Calloway| first1=Colin| title=The American Revolution in Indian Country: Crisis and Diversity in Native American Communities| date=1995| publisher=Cambridge University Press| isbn=978-0-521-47149-7| pages=[https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti00call/page/88 88\u2013107]| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti00call/page/88}}</ref>\n\nIn the eighteenth century, some of the Mohicans developed strong ties with missionaries of the [[Moravian Church]] from [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]], who founded a mission at their village of {{lang|mjy|[[Shekomeko]]}} in [[Dutchess County, New York]]. Henry Rauch reached out to two Mohican leaders, {{lang|mjy|Maumauntissekun}}, also known as {{lang|mjy|Shabash}}; and {{lang|mjy|Wassamapah}}, who took him back to Shekomeko. They named him the new religious teacher. Over time, Rauch won listeners, as the Mohicans had suffered much from disease and warfare, which had disrupted their society. Early in 1742, Shabash and two other Mohicans accompanied Rauch to Bethlehem, where he was to be ordained as a deacon. The three Mohicans were baptized on 11 February 1742 in John de Turk's barn nearby at [[Oley, Pennsylvania]]. Shabash was the first Mohican of Shekomeko to adopt the Christian religion.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|title=The Mohican World 1680\u20131750|year=2000|pages=228\u2013230}}</ref> The Moravians built a chapel for the Mohican people in 1743. They defended the Mohican against European settlers' exploitation, trying to protect them against land encroachment and abuses of liquor.\n\nOn a 1738 visit to New York, the Mohicans spoke to Governor [[Lewis Morris (governor)|Lewis Morris]] concerning the sale of their land near Shekomeko. The Governor promised they would be paid as soon as the lands were surveyed.  He suggested that for their own security, they should mark off their square mile of land they wished to keep, which the Mohicans never did. In September 1743, still under the Acting-Governor [[George Clarke (governor)|George Clarke]] the land was finally surveyed by New York Assembly agents and divided into lots, a row of which ran through the Indians' reserved land. With some help from the missionaries, on 17 October 1743 and already under the new Royal Governor [[George Clinton (Royal Navy officer)|George Clinton]], Shabash put together a petition of names of people who could attest that the land in which one of the lots was running through was theirs. Despite Shabash's appeals, his persistence, and the missionaries' help, the Mohicans lost the case.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|title=The Mohican World 1680\u20131750|year=2000|pages=232\u2013235}}</ref> The lots were eventually bought up by European-American settlers and the Mohicans were forced out of Shekomeko. Some who opposed the missionaries' work accused them of being secret [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] (who had been outlawed from the colony in 1700) and of working with the Mohicans on the side of the French. The missionaries were summoned more than once before colonial government, but also had supporters. In the late 1740s the colonial government at [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]] expelled the missionaries from New York, in part because of their advocacy of Mohican rights. Settlers soon took over the Mohican land.<ref>[http://www.usgennet.org/usa/ny/town/pineplains/history.html Philip H. Smith, \"Pine Plains\"], ''General History of Duchess County from 1609 to 1876, inclusive'', Pawling, NY: 1877, accessed 3 March 2010</ref>\n\n===Revolutionary War===\n[[File:Stockbridge 1778.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Von Ewald sketch of a [[Stockbridge Militia]] Mohican warrior who fought on the Patriot side in the [[Continental Army]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]]]]\n\nIn August 1775, the [[Iroquois Confederacy|Six Nations]] staged a council fire near Albany, after news of Bunker Hill had made war seem imminent. After much debate, they decided that such a war was a private affair between the British and the colonists (known as Rebels, Revolutionaries, Congress-Men, American Whigs, or [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriots]]), and that they should stay out of it. Mohawk Chief [[Joseph Brant]] feared that the Indians would lose their lands if the Colonists achieved independence. Sir [[Sir William Johnson, 1st Baronet|William Johnson]], his son [[Sir John Johnson, 2nd Baronet|John Johnson]] and son-in-law [[Guy Johnson]] and Brant used all their influence to engage the Iroquois to fight for the British cause. The [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]], [[Onondaga people|Onondaga]], [[Cayuga people|Cayuga]], and [[Seneca people|Seneca]] ultimately became allies and provided warriors for the battles in the New York area. The [[Oneida people|Oneida]] and [[Tuscarora people|Tuscarora]] sided with the Colonists. The Mohicans, who as Algonquians were not part of the Iroquois Confederacy, sided with the Patriots, serving at the Siege of Boston, and the battles of Saratoga and Monmouth.\n\nIn 1778 they lost fifteen warriors in a British ambush at the Bronx, New York, and later received a commendation from George Washington.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aupaumut|first1=Hendrick|title=From George Washington to Captain Hendrick Aupaumut, 4 July 1779|url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Washington/03-21-02-0283|publisher=Archives.gov}}</ref>\n\nLater, the citizens of the new United States forced many Native Americans off their land and westward. In the 1780s, groups of Stockbridge Indians moved from Massachusetts to a new location among the [[Oneida people]] in western New York, who were granted a {{convert|300000|acre|adj=on}} reservation for their service to the Patriots, out of their former territory of {{convert|6000000|acre}}. They called their settlement New Stockbridge. Some individuals and families, mostly people who were old or those with special ties to the area, remained behind at Stockbridge.\n\nThe central figures of Mohican society, including the chief sachem, Joseph Quanaukaunt, and his counselors and relatives, were part of the move to New Stockbridge. At the new town, the Stockbridge emigrants controlled their own affairs and combined traditional ways with the new as they chose. After learning from the Christian missionaries, the Stockbridge Indians were experienced in English ways. At [[Stockbridge, New York|New Stockbridge]] they replicated their former town. While continuing as Christians, they retained their language and Mohican cultural traditions. In general, their evolving Mohican identity was still rooted in traditions of the past.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|first=Shirley|title=The Mohican World 1680\u20131750|year=2000|publisher=Purple Mountain Press, Ltd.|location=Fleischmanns, New York|pages=213}}</ref>\n\n==Removal to Wisconsin==\nIn the 1820s and 1830s, most of the Stockbridge Indians moved to [[Shawano County, Wisconsin]], where they were promised land by the US government under the policy of [[Indian removal]]. In Wisconsin, they settled on [[Indian reservation|reservation]]s with the [[Lenape]] (called Munsee after one of their major dialects), who were also speakers of one of the Algonquian languages.  Together, the two formed a band and are federally recognized as the [[Stockbridge-Munsee Community]].\n\nThe now extinct [[Mohican language]] belonged to the [[Eastern Algonquian languages|Eastern Algonquian]] branch of the [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian language]] family. It was an Algonquian N-dialect, as were [[Massachusett]] and [[Wampanoag language|Wampanoag]]. In many ways, it was similar to one of the L-dialects, like that of the [[Lenape]], and could be considered one.\n\nTheir 22,000-acre reservation is known as that of the Stockbridge-Munsee Band of Mohican Indians and is located near the town of [[Bowler, Wisconsin|Bowler]]. Since the late twentieth century, they have developed the North Star Mohican Resort and Casino on their reservation, which has successfully generated funds for tribal welfare and economic development.<ref name=\"Toensing\"/>\n\n==Land claims==\nIn the late twentieth century, the Stockbridge-Munsee were among tribes filing land claims against New York, which had been ruled to have unconstitutionally acquired land from Indians without Senate ratification. The Stockbridge-Munsee filed a land claim against New York state for {{convert|23000|acre}} in Madison County, the location of its former property. In 2011, outgoing governor [[David Paterson]] announced having reached a deal with the tribe. They would be given nearly {{convert|2|acre}} in Madison County and give up their larger claim in exchange for the state's giving them 330 acres of land in [[Sullivan County, New York|Sullivan County]] in the [[Catskill Mountains]], where the government was trying to encourage economic development. The federal government had agreed to take the land in trust, making it eligible for development as a gaming casino, and the state would allow gaming, an increasingly important source of revenue for American Indians. Race track and casinos, private interests and other tribes opposed the deal.<ref name=\"Toensing\">[https://archive.is/20130126040651/http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/2011/01/26/seneca-nation-cries-foul-over-n-y-agreement-to-give-casino-to-wisc-tribe-12651 Gale Courey Toensing, \"Seneca Upset Over N.Y. Casino Agreement\"], ''Indian Country Today'', 26 January 2011</ref>\n\n==Representation in media==\n[[James Fenimore Cooper]] based his novel, ''[[The Last of the Mohicans]]'', on the Mohican tribe. His description includes some cultural aspects of the [[Mohegan]], a different Algonquian tribe that lived in eastern [[Connecticut]]. Cooper set his novel in the Hudson Valley, Mohican land, but used some Mohegan names for his characters, such as [[Uncas]].\n\nThe novel has been adapted for the cinema more than a dozen times, the first time in 1920. [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]] directed a [[The Last of the Mohicans (1992 film)|1992 adaptation]], which starred [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] as a Mohican-adopted white man.\n\n==Notable members==\n* [[Hendrick Aupaumut]], (1757\u20131830) sachem, historian, and [[American Revolutionary War]] captain\n* [[Steve Conliff]], (1949-2006) political writer, historian, [[Yippie]] activist\n* [[Brent Michael Davids]], (b. 1959) composer/flautist \n* [[Anthony Kiedis]], (b. 1962) singer for [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Keidis |first1=Anthony|first2=Larry|last2=Sloman |date=2004 |title= Scar Tissue|publisher=Hachette Books |page= }}</ref>\n* [[Bill Miller (musician)|Bill Miller]], (b. 1955) musician\n* [[Electa Quinney]], (1798\u20131885) first public teacher and school mistress in [[Wisconsin]]\n* [[John Wannuaucon Quinney]], (1797\u20131855) diplomat\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Aupaumut, Hendrick. (1790). [https://books.google.com/books?id=yKZbSG-NJzIC&pg=PA64 \"History of the Muh-he-con-nuk Indians\", in ''American Indian Nonfiction, An Anthology of Writings, 1760s\u20131930s'' (pp. 63\u201371). Norman: University of Oklahoma Press.]\n* Nekatcit. ''The Celestial Bear Comes Down to Earth: The Bear Sacrifice Ceremony of the Munsee-Mahican in Canada as Related by Nekatcit'' Edited by Frank G. Speck in collaboration with Jesse Moses, Delaware Nation. Pub. 1945, Reading Public Museum.\n* Jones, Electa. (1854). [https://ia802704.us.archive.org/17/items/stockbridgepast00jonegoog/stockbridgepast00jonegoog.pdf \"Stockbridge Past and Present\".]\n* Ruttenber, E. M. (1872). [https://archive.org/details/ruttenberindians00ruttrich \"History of the Indian Tribes of Hudson's River; Their Origin, Manners and Customs; Tribal and Sub-Tribal Organizations; Wars, Treaties, Etc., Etc.\"  Albany: J. Munsell History Series.]\n* Starna, William A.: ''From Homeland to New Land: A History of the Mahican Indians, 1600\u20131830.'' University of Nebraska Press, 2013. {{ISBN|978-0803244955}}\n* Brasser, T. J. (1978). \"Mahican\", in B. G. Trigger (Ed.), ''Northeast'' (pp.&nbsp;198\u2013212). ''Handbook of North American Indian languages'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Cappel, Constance, \"The Smallpox Genocide of the Odawa Tribe at L'Arbre Croche, 1763\", ''The History of a Native American People'', Lewiston, NY: The Edwin Mellen Press, 2007.\n* Conkey, Laura E.; Bolissevain, Ethel; & Goddard, Ives. (1978). \"Indians of southern New England and Long Island: Late period\", in B. G. Trigger (Ed.), ''Northeast'' (pp.&nbsp;177\u2013189). ''Handbook of North American Indian languages'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Salwen, Bert. (1978). \"Indians of southern New England and Long Island: Early period\", in B. G. Trigger (Ed.), ''Northeast'' (pp.&nbsp;160\u2013176). ''Handbook of North American Indian languages'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Simpson, J. A.; & Weiner, E. S. C. (1989). \"Mohican\", ''Oxford English Dictionary''. Oxford: Clarendon Press. (Online version).\n* Sturtevant, William C. (Ed.). (1978\u2013present). ''Handbook of North American Indians'' (Vol. 1\u201320). Washington, D. C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Trigger, Bruce G. (Ed.). (1978). ''Northeast'', ''Handbook of North American Indians'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D. C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mahican}}\n* [http://www.mohican.com/ Stockbridge-Munsee community]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120822023701/http://www.mohican-nsn.gov/Departments/Library-Museum/Mohican_History/origin-and-early.htm Mohican nation Stockbridge-Munsee band: Our history]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100111075910/http://wolfweb.unr.edu/homepage/shubinsk/mohican.html Mohican Indians]\n\n{{Capital District}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mohican}}\n[[Category:Algonquian peoples]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Shawano County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Stockbridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Algonquian ethnonyms]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of North America]]\n[[Category:People of New Netherland]]\n[[Category:American Indian reservations in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Native Americans in the American Revolution]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Mohican}}\n{{distinguish|text=the [[Mohegan]]s, a different Algonquian-speaking tribe living in eastern (upper Thames valley) Connecticut}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group         = Mohicans<br/><small>{{lang|mjy|Muhhekunneuw}}</small>\n|image         = File:Mohican distribution map.svg\n|image_caption = Historic territory of the Mohicans\n|pop           = {{circa}} 3,000\n|popplace      = {{USA}} ([[Shawano County, Wisconsin]])\n|langs         = [[English language|English]] (originally [[Mohican language|Mohican]])\n|rels          = [[Moravian Church]]\n|related       = [[Lenape]], [[Mohegan]], [[Pequot]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Mohicans''' ({{IPAc-en|m|o\u028a|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|k|\u0259n|s}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|k|\u0259n|s}}, alternate spelling: Mahican) are an [[Eastern Algonquian]] [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[Native Americans in the United States|tribe]] that was Algonquian-speaking. As part of the Eastern Algonquian family of tribes, they are related to the abutting [[Lenape]], who occupied territory to the south as far as the Atlantic coast. The Mohicans occupied the upper tidal [[Hudson River Valley]], including the confluence of the Mohawk River (where present-day [[Albany, New York]], developed) and into western New England centered on the upper Housatonic watershed. After 1680, due to conflicts with the [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]] during the [[Beaver Wars]], many were driven southeastward across the present-day Massachusetts western border and the [[Taconic Mountains]] to [[Berkshire County]] around [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]].\n \nSince the forcible relocation of American Indian populations to reservations in the [[American Frontier|American West]] during the 1830s, most descendants of the Mohicans are located in [[Shawano County, Wisconsin]].  Decades later they eventually formed the federally recognized [[Stockbridge-Munsee Community]] with registered members of the [[Munsee]] people and have a {{convert|22000|acre|km2|adj=on|0}} reservation.\n\nFollowing the disruption of the [[American Revolutionary War]], most of the Mohican descendants first migrated westward to join the [[Iroquois]] [[Oneida people|Oneida]] on their reservation in central New York. The Oneida gave them about 22,000 acres for their use. After more than two decades, in the 1820s and 1830s, the Oneida and the Stockbridge moved again, pressured to relocate to northeastern [[Wisconsin]] under the federal [[Indian Removal]] program.<ref name=EBmohs>[http://p2.www.britannica.com/ebc/article-9370993 EB-Mohicans \"Mohican\" (history)], ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', 2007 {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20070624083706/http://p2.www.britannica.com/ebc/article-9370993 |date=24 June 2007 }}</ref> A group of Mohicans also migrated to Canada to live with Iroquois Six Nations.\n\nThe tribe identified by the place where they lived: {{lang|mjy|Muh-he-ka-neew}} (or \"people of the continually flowing waters\").<ref>''Stockbridge, Past and Present''; Electa Jones</ref> The word {{lang|mjy|Muh-he-kan}} refers to a great sea or body of water, and the Hudson River reminded them of their place of origin, so they named the Hudson River {{lang|mjy|Mahicanituck}}, or the river where there are people from the continually flowing waters.<ref>\"Mohican Oral Tribal History as recorded by Hendrick Aupaumut\" and printed in ''Stockbridge, Past and Present'' by Electa Jones.</ref> Therefore, they, along with other tribes living along the Hudson River (such as the ''[[Munsee]]'', known by the dialect of Lenape that they spoke, and ''[[Wappinger]]''), were called \"the River Indians\" by the Dutch and English. The Dutch heard and wrote the term for the people of the area variously as: ''Mahigan'', ''Mahikander'', ''Mahinganak'', ''Maikan'' and ''Mawhickon'', among other variants, which the English simplified later to ''Mohican'' or ''Mahican'', in a transliteration to their spelling system. The French, adopting names used by their Indian allies in Canada, knew the Mohicans as the {{lang|fr|Loups}} (or wolves); similarly, they referred to the [[Iroquois]] as the \"Snake People\" (or \"Five Nations\").  Like the Munsee and Wappinger peoples, the Mohicans were related to the [[Lenape people]], who occupied coastal areas from western Long Island to the [[Delaware River]] valley to the south.\n\nIn the late twentieth century, the Mohicans joined other former New York tribes and the Oneida in filing land claims against New York state for what were considered unconstitutional purchases after the Revolutionary War. In 2010, outgoing governor [[David Paterson]] announced a land exchange with the Stockbridge-Munsee that would enable them to build a large casino on {{convert|330|acre}} in [[Sullivan County, New York|Sullivan County]] in the [[Catskills]], in exchange for dropping their larger claim in [[Madison County, New York|Madison County]]. The deal had many opponents.\n\n==Territory==\nThe Mohicans were living in and around the [[Hudson River]] (or {{lang|mjy|Mahicannituck}}) at the time of their first contact with [[Europe]]ans traders along the river in the 1590s. After 1609 at the time of the Dutch settlement of [[New Netherland]], they also ranged along the eastern [[Mohawk River]] and the [[Hoosic River]]. Most of their communities lay along the upper tidal reaches of the Hudson River and along the watersheds of Kinderhook-Claverack-Taghkanic Creek, the Roeliff Jansen Kill, Catskil Creek, and adjacent areas of the Housatonic Watershed. Mohican territory reached along Hudson River watersheds northeastward to Wood Creek just south of [[Lake Champlain]]. In [[Mohican language|their own language]], the Mohicans identified collectively as the {{lang|mjy|Muhhekunneuw}}, \"people of the great tidal river\".<ref name=sultzman>[http://www.dickshovel.com/Mahican.html Sultzman, Lee. \"Mahican History\"]</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nMohican villages were fairly large. Usually consisting of 20 to 30 mid-sized [[longhouse]]s, they were located on hills and heavily fortified. Their large cornfields were located nearby. Agriculture and gathering of nuts, fruits and roots provided most of their diet, but was supplemented by the men hunting game, and fishing. Mohican villages were governed by hereditary [[sachem]]s advised by a council of clan elders. A general council of sachems met regularly at [[Schodack, New York|Shodac]] (east of present-day Albany) to decide important matters affecting the entire confederacy.<ref name=sultzman/> In his history of the Indians of the Hudson River, [[Edward Manning Ruttenber]] described the clans of the Mohicans as the Bear, the Turkey, the Turtle, and the Wolf, with the Wolf serving as a defensive shield in the north against the Mohawk.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nLike their Munsee-speaking relatives to the south, Mohican villages followed a dispersed settlement pattern, with each community likely dominated by a single lineage or clan. Usually consisting of a small cluster of small and mid-sized [[longhouse]]s, they were located along floodplains. During times of war, they built fortifications in defensive locations (such as along ridges) as places of retreat. Their cornfields were located near to their communities; varieties of squash, beans, sunflowers, and other crops from the [[Eastern Agricultural Complex]]. Horticulture and gathering of nuts (hickory, butternuts, black walnuts and acorns), fruits (blueberries, raspberries, juneberries among many others) and roots (groundnuts, wood lilies, arrowroot among others) provided much of their diet. This was supplemented by the men hunting game (turkeys, deer, elk, bears, and moose in the Taconics) and fishing (sturgeon, alewives, shad, eels, lamprey and striped bass). Mohican communities were governed by hereditary [[sachem]]s advised by a council of clan elders. A general council of sachems met regularly at [[Schodack, New York|Schodac]] (east of present-day Albany) to decide important matters affecting the entire group.<ref name=sultzman/> Moravian missionary [[John Heckewelder]] and early anthropologist [[Lewis H. Morgan]] both learned, from Mohican informants, that their matrilineal society was divided into three phratries (Turkey, Turtle and Wolf) and these divided into clans or subclans, including a potentially prominent Bear Clan. This is supported by Mohican signatures on treaties and land deeds (see the works of [[Shirley Dunn]]).\n\n==History==\n===Mohican Confederacy===\nThe Mohicans were a confederacy of five tribes and as many as forty villages.<ref name=sultzman/>\n* ''Mohican proper'', lived in the vicinity of today's [[Albany, New York|Albany]] ({{lang|mjy|Pempotowwuthut-Muhhcanneuw}}, \"the fireplace of the Mahican Nation\") west towards the Mohawk River and to the northwest to Lake Champlain and Lake George\n* {{lang|mjy|Mechkentowoon}}, lived along the west shore of the Hudson River above the Catskill Creek)\n* {{lang|mjy|Wawyachtonoc}} (or {{lang|mjy|Wawayachtonoc}},  \"eddy people\" or \"people of the curving channel\"), lived in [[Dutchess County, New York|Dutchess County]] and [[Columbia County, New York|Columbia County]] eastward to the Housatonic River in [[Litchfield County, Connecticut|Litchfield County]], Connecticut, main village was ''Weantinock'', additional villages: ''Shecomeco'', ''Wechquadnach'', ''Pamperaug'', ''Bantam'', ''Weataug'', ''Scaticook'')\n* ''Westenhuck'' (from {{lang|mjy|hous atenuc}}, \"on the other side of the mountains\"), the name of a village near [[Great Barrington, Massachusetts|Great Barrington]], Massachusetts. Often called the \"[[Housatonic Valley|Housatonic people]],\" they lived in the [[Housatonic Valley]] in Connecticut and Massachusetts and in the vicinity of Great Barrington, which they called {{lang|mjy|Mahaiwe}}, meaning \"the place downstream\"<ref>Donald B. Ricky: ''Indians of Maryland Past and Present'', Verlag: Somerset Pubs, 1999; {{ISBN|978-0403098774}}</ref>\n* ''Wiekagjoc'' (from {{lang|mjy|wikwajek}}, \"upper reaches of a river\"), lived east of the Hudson Rivers near the city of [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]], Columbia County, New York<ref>Allen W. Trelease, William A. Starna: ''Indian Affairs in Colonial New York Indian Affairs in Colonial New York:'' The Seventeenth Century the Seventeenth Century, Seite 8, University of Nebraska Press; 1997, {{ISBN|978-0803294318}}</ref>\n\n=== Conflict with the Mohawk ===\n[[File:Land deed, May 31, 1664, Willem Hoffmeyer purchase of 3 islands in the Hudson River near Troy from three native Mahicans - Albany Institute of History and Art - DSC07971.JPG|thumb|Land deed, 31 May 1664, Willem Hoffmeyer purchase of 3 islands in the Hudson River near Troy from three native Mohicans \u2013 Albany Institute of History and Art]]\n\nThe Algonquians (Mohican) and Iroquois (Mohawk) were traditional competitors and enemies. Iroquois oral tradition, as recorded in the ''[[Jesuit Relations]]'', speaks of a war between the Mohawks and an alliance of the Susquehannock and [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] (sometime between 1580 and 1600). This was perhaps in response to the formation of the League of the Iroquois.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/americanheritage00bran Brandon, William. ''American Heritage Book of Indians'', (Alvin M. Josephy, ed.), American Heritage Pub. Co. 1961, p. 187]</ref>\n\nIn September 1609 Henry Hudson encountered Mohican villages just below present day Albany, with whom he traded goods for furs. Hudson returned to Holland with a cargo of valuable furs which immediately attracted Dutch merchants to the area. The first Dutch fur traders arrived on the Hudson River the following year to trade with the Mohicans. Besides exposing them to European epidemics, the fur trade destabilized the region.<ref name=sultzman/>\n\nIn 1614, the Dutch decided to establish a permanent trading post on [[Castle Island (New York)|Castle Island]], on the site of a previous French post that had been long abandoned; but first they had to arrange a truce to end fighting which had broken out between the Mohicans and Mohawks. Fighting broke out again between the Mohicans and Mohawks in 1617, and with [[Fort Nassau (North River)|Fort Nassau]] badly damaged by a freshet, the Dutch abandoned the fort. In 1618, having once again negotiated a truce, the Dutch rebuilt Fort Nassau on higher ground.<ref>[http://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsAmericas/NorthMohicans.htm \"Mahican Confederacy\", The History Files]</ref> Late that year, Fort Nassau was destroyed by flooding and abandoned for good. In 1624, Captain [[Cornelius Jacobsen May]] sailed the {{lang|nl|Nieuw Nederlandt}} upriver and landed eighteen families of [[Walloons]] on a plain opposite Castle Island. They commenced to construct [[Fort Orange (New Netherland)|Fort Orange]].\n\nThe Mohicans invited the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] and [[Innu|Montagnais]] to bring their furs to Fort Orange as an alternate to French traders in Quebec. Seeing the Mohicans extended their control over the fur trade, the Mohawk attacked, with initial success. In 1625 or 1626 the Mohicans destroyed the easternmost Iroquois \"castle\". The Mohawks then re-located south of the [[Mohawk River]], closer to Fort Orange. In July 1626 many of the settlers moved to [[New Amsterdam]] because of the conflict. The Mohicans requested help from the Dutch and Commander Daniel Van Krieckebeek set out from the fort with six soldiers. Van Krieckebeek, three soldiers, and twenty-four Mohicans were killed when their party was ambushed by the Mohawk about mile from the fort. The Mohawks withdrew with some body parts of those slain for later consumption as a demonstration of supremacy.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qJ-KAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA115 Parmenter, Jon W., \"Separate Vessels\", ''The Worlds of the Seventeenth-Century Hudson Valley'', (Jaap Jacobs, L. H. Roper, eds.) SUNY Press, 2014, {{ISBN|9781438450971}}][[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]]&nbsp;[[Special:BookSources/9781438450971|9781438450971]][[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]]&nbsp;[[Special:BookSources/9781438450971|9781438450971]]<span> p. 113</span></ref>\n\nWar continued to rage between the Mohicans and Mohawks throughout the area from Skahn\u00e9htati ([[Schenectady, New York|Schenectady]]) to Kinderhoek [[Kinderhook (village), New York|Kinderhook]].<ref name=Chronicle>[https://books.google.com/books?id=XNU0AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=albany+chronicles&q=orange Reynolds, Cuyler. ''Albany Chronicles: A History of the City Arranged Chronologically'', J.B. Lyon Company, 1906]{{PD-notice}}</ref> By 1629, the Mohawks had taken over territories on the west bank of the Hudson River that were formerly held by the Mohicans.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Mohawk_Frontier.html?id=xWsq2NPeYRcC Burke Jr, T. E., & Starna, W. A. (1991). ''Mohawk Frontier: The Dutch Community of Schenectady, New York, 1661\u20131710''], SUNY Press. p. 26</ref> The conflict caused most of the Mohican to migrate eastward across the [[Hudson River]] into western Massachusetts and Connecticut.  The Mohawks gained a near-monopoly in the fur trade with the Dutch by prohibiting the nearby Algonquian-speaking tribes to the north or east to trade.\n\n===Stockbridge===\nMany Mohicans settled in the town of [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], where they gradually became known as the \"Stockbridge Indians\". {{lang|mjy|Etow Oh Koam}}, one of their chiefs, accompanied three Mohawk chiefs on a state visit to [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] and her government in England in 1710. They were popularly referred to as the [[Four Mohawk Kings]].\n\n[[File:Mohawk king engraving.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Mohican chief {{lang|mjy|Etow Oh Koam}}, referred to as one of the [[Four Mohawk Kings]] in a state visit to [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] in 1710. By [[John Simon (engraver)|John Simon]], c. 1750.]]\nThe Stockbridge Indians allowed [[Protestant]] [[missionary|missionaries]], including [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Jonathan Edwards]], to live among them.  In the 18th century, many converted to [[Christianity]], while keeping certain traditions of their own.  They fought on the side of the British colonists in the [[French and Indian War]] (also known as the [[Seven Years' War]]).  During the [[American Revolution]], they sided with the colonists.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Calloway| first1=Colin| title=The American Revolution in Indian Country: Crisis and Diversity in Native American Communities| date=1995| publisher=Cambridge University Press| isbn=978-0-521-47149-7| pages=[https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti00call/page/88 88\u2013107]| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/americanrevoluti00call/page/88}}</ref>\n\nIn the eighteenth century, some of the Mohicans developed strong ties with missionaries of the [[Moravian Church]] from [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]], who founded a mission at their village of {{lang|mjy|[[Shekomeko]]}} in [[Dutchess County, New York]]. Henry Rauch reached out to two Mohican leaders, {{lang|mjy|Maumauntissekun}}, also known as {{lang|mjy|Shabash}}; and {{lang|mjy|Wassamapah}}, who took him back to Shekomeko. They named him the new religious teacher. Over time, Rauch won listeners, as the Mohicans had suffered much from disease and warfare, which had disrupted their society. Early in 1742, Shabash and two other Mohicans accompanied Rauch to Bethlehem, where he was to be ordained as a deacon. The three Mohicans were baptized on 11 February 1742 in John de Turk's barn nearby at [[Oley, Pennsylvania]]. Shabash was the first Mohican of Shekomeko to adopt the Christian religion.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|title=The Mohican World 1680\u20131750|year=2000|pages=228\u2013230}}</ref> The Moravians built a chapel for the Mohican people in 1743. They defended the Mohican against European settlers' exploitation, trying to protect them against land encroachment and abuses of liquor.\n\nOn a 1738 visit to New York, the Mohicans spoke to Governor [[Lewis Morris (governor)|Lewis Morris]] concerning the sale of their land near Shekomeko. The Governor promised they would be paid as soon as the lands were surveyed.  He suggested that for their own security, they should mark off their square mile of land they wished to keep, which the Mohicans never did. In September 1743, still under the Acting-Governor [[George Clarke (governor)|George Clarke]] the land was finally surveyed by New York Assembly agents and divided into lots, a row of which ran through the Indians' reserved land. With some help from the missionaries, on 17 October 1743 and already under the new Royal Governor [[George Clinton (Royal Navy officer)|George Clinton]], Shabash put together a petition of names of people who could attest that the land in which one of the lots was running through was theirs. Despite Shabash's appeals, his persistence, and the missionaries' help, the Mohicans lost the case.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|title=The Mohican World 1680\u20131750|year=2000|pages=232\u2013235}}</ref> The lots were eventually bought up by European-American settlers and the Mohicans were forced out of Shekomeko. Some who opposed the missionaries' work accused them of being secret [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] (who had been outlawed from the colony in 1700) and of working with the Mohicans on the side of the French. The missionaries were summoned more than once before colonial government, but also had supporters. In the late 1740s the colonial government at [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]] expelled the missionaries from New York, in part because of their advocacy of Mohican rights. Settlers soon took over the Mohican land.<ref>[http://www.usgennet.org/usa/ny/town/pineplains/history.html Philip H. Smith, \"Pine Plains\"], ''General History of Duchess County from 1609 to 1876, inclusive'', Pawling, NY: 1877, accessed 3 March 2010</ref>\n\n===Revolutionary War===\n[[File:Stockbridge 1778.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Von Ewald sketch of a [[Stockbridge Militia]] Mohican warrior who fought on the Patriot side in the [[Continental Army]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]]]]\n\nIn August 1775, the [[Iroquois Confederacy|Six Nations]] staged a council fire near Albany, after news of Bunker Hill had made war seem imminent. After much debate, they decided that such a war was a private affair between the British and the colonists (known as Rebels, Revolutionaries, Congress-Men, American Whigs, or [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriots]]), and that they should stay out of it. Mohawk Chief [[Joseph Brant]] feared that the Indians would lose their lands if the Colonists achieved independence. Sir [[Sir William Johnson, 1st Baronet|William Johnson]], his son [[Sir John Johnson, 2nd Baronet|John Johnson]] and son-in-law [[Guy Johnson]] and Brant used all their influence to engage the Iroquois to fight for the British cause. The [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]], [[Onondaga people|Onondaga]], [[Cayuga people|Cayuga]], and [[Seneca people|Seneca]] ultimately became allies and provided warriors for the battles in the New York area. The [[Oneida people|Oneida]] and [[Tuscarora people|Tuscarora]] sided with the Colonists. The Mohicans, who as Algonquians were not part of the Iroquois Confederacy, sided with the Patriots, serving at the Siege of Boston, and the battles of Saratoga and Monmouth.\n\nIn 1778 they lost fifteen warriors in a British ambush at the Bronx, New York, and later received a commendation from George Washington.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aupaumut|first1=Hendrick|title=From George Washington to Captain Hendrick Aupaumut, 4 July 1779|url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Washington/03-21-02-0283|publisher=Archives.gov}}</ref>\n\nLater, the citizens of the new United States forced many Native Americans off their land and westward. In the 1780s, groups of Stockbridge Indians moved from Massachusetts to a new location among the [[Oneida people]] in western New York, who were granted a {{convert|300000|acre|adj=on}} reservation for their service to the Patriots, out of their former territory of {{convert|6000000|acre}}. They called their settlement New Stockbridge. Some individuals and families, mostly people who were old or those with special ties to the area, remained behind at Stockbridge.\n\nThe central figures of Mohican society, including the chief sachem, Joseph Quanaukaunt, and his counselors and relatives, were part of the move to New Stockbridge. At the new town, the Stockbridge emigrants controlled their own affairs and combined traditional ways with the new as they chose. After learning from the Christian missionaries, the Stockbridge Indians were experienced in English ways. At [[Stockbridge, New York|New Stockbridge]] they replicated their former town. While continuing as Christians, they retained their language and Mohican cultural traditions. In general, their evolving Mohican identity was still rooted in traditions of the past.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunn|first=Shirley|title=The Mohican World 1680\u20131750|year=2000|publisher=Purple Mountain Press, Ltd.|location=Fleischmanns, New York|pages=213}}</ref>\n\n==Removal to Wisconsin==\nIn the 1820s and 1830s, most of the Stockbridge Indians moved to [[Shawano County, Wisconsin]], where they were promised land by the US government under the policy of [[Indian removal]]. In Wisconsin, they settled on [[Indian reservation|reservation]]s with the [[Lenape]] (called Munsee after one of their major dialects), who were also speakers of one of the Algonquian languages.  Together, the two formed a band and are federally recognized as the [[Stockbridge-Munsee Community]].\n\nThe now extinct [[Mohican language]] belonged to the [[Eastern Algonquian languages|Eastern Algonquian]] branch of the [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian language]] family. It was an Algonquian N-dialect, as were [[Massachusett]] and [[Wampanoag language|Wampanoag]]. In many ways, it was similar to one of the L-dialects, like that of the [[Lenape]], and could be considered one.\n\nTheir 22,000-acre reservation is known as that of the Stockbridge-Munsee Band of Mohican Indians and is located near the town of [[Bowler, Wisconsin|Bowler]]. Since the late twentieth century, they have developed the North Star Mohican Resort and Casino on their reservation, which has successfully generated funds for tribal welfare and economic development.<ref name=\"Toensing\"/>\n\n==Land claims==\nIn the late twentieth century, the Stockbridge-Munsee were among tribes filing land claims against New York, which had been ruled to have unconstitutionally acquired land from Indians without Senate ratification. The Stockbridge-Munsee filed a land claim against New York state for {{convert|23000|acre}} in Madison County, the location of its former property. In 2011, outgoing governor [[David Paterson]] announced having reached a deal with the tribe. They would be given nearly {{convert|2|acre}} in Madison County and give up their larger claim in exchange for the state's giving them 330 acres of land in [[Sullivan County, New York|Sullivan County]] in the [[Catskill Mountains]], where the government was trying to encourage economic development. The federal government had agreed to take the land in trust, making it eligible for development as a gaming casino, and the state would allow gaming, an increasingly important source of revenue for American Indians. Race track and casinos, private interests and other tribes opposed the deal.<ref name=\"Toensing\">[https://archive.is/20130126040651/http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/2011/01/26/seneca-nation-cries-foul-over-n-y-agreement-to-give-casino-to-wisc-tribe-12651 Gale Courey Toensing, \"Seneca Upset Over N.Y. Casino Agreement\"], ''Indian Country Today'', 26 January 2011</ref>\n\n==Representation in media==\n[[James Fenimore Cooper]] based his novel, ''[[The Last of the Mohicans]]'', on the Mohican tribe. His description includes some cultural aspects of the [[Mohegan]], a different Algonquian tribe that lived in eastern [[Connecticut]]. Cooper set his novel in the Hudson Valley, Mohican land, but used some Mohegan names for his characters, such as [[Uncas]].\n\nThe novel has been adapted for the cinema more than a dozen times, the first time in 1920. [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]] directed a [[The Last of the Mohicans (1992 film)|1992 adaptation]], which starred [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] as a Mohican-adopted white man.\n\n==Notable members==\n* [[Hendrick Aupaumut]], (1757\u20131830) sachem, historian, and [[American Revolutionary War]] captain\n* [[Steve Conliff]], (1949-2006) political writer, historian, [[Yippie]] activist\n* [[Brent Michael Davids]], (b. 1959) composer/flautist \n* [[Anthony Kiedis]], (b. 1962) singer for [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Keidis |first1=Anthony|first2=Larry|last2=Sloman |date=2004 |title= Scar Tissue|publisher=Hachette Books |page= }}</ref>\n* [[Bill Miller (musician)|Bill Miller]], (b. 1955) musician\n* [[Electa Quinney]], (1798\u20131885) first public teacher and school mistress in [[Wisconsin]]\n* [[John Wannuaucon Quinney]], (1797\u20131855) diplomat\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Aupaumut, Hendrick. (1790). [https://books.google.com/books?id=yKZbSG-NJzIC&pg=PA64 \"History of the Muh-he-con-nuk Indians\", in ''American Indian Nonfiction, An Anthology of Writings, 1760s\u20131930s'' (pp. 63\u201371). Norman: University of Oklahoma Press.]\n* Nekatcit. ''The Celestial Bear Comes Down to Earth: The Bear Sacrifice Ceremony of the Munsee-Mahican in Canada as Related by Nekatcit'' Edited by Frank G. Speck in collaboration with Jesse Moses, Delaware Nation. Pub. 1945, Reading Public Museum.\n* Jones, Electa. (1854). [https://ia802704.us.archive.org/17/items/stockbridgepast00jonegoog/stockbridgepast00jonegoog.pdf \"Stockbridge Past and Present\".]\n* Ruttenber, E. M. (1872). [https://archive.org/details/ruttenberindians00ruttrich \"History of the Indian Tribes of Hudson's River; Their Origin, Manners and Customs; Tribal and Sub-Tribal Organizations; Wars, Treaties, Etc., Etc.\"  Albany: J. Munsell History Series.]\n* Starna, William A.: ''From Homeland to New Land: A History of the Mahican Indians, 1600\u20131830.'' University of Nebraska Press, 2013. {{ISBN|978-0803244955}}\n* Brasser, T. J. (1978). \"Mahican\", in B. G. Trigger (Ed.), ''Northeast'' (pp.&nbsp;198\u2013212). ''Handbook of North American Indian languages'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Cappel, Constance, \"The Smallpox Genocide of the Odawa Tribe at L'Arbre Croche, 1763\", ''The History of a Native American People'', Lewiston, NY: The Edwin Mellen Press, 2007.\n* Conkey, Laura E.; Bolissevain, Ethel; & Goddard, Ives. (1978). \"Indians of southern New England and Long Island: Late period\", in B. G. Trigger (Ed.), ''Northeast'' (pp.&nbsp;177\u2013189). ''Handbook of North American Indian languages'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Salwen, Bert. (1978). \"Indians of southern New England and Long Island: Early period\", in B. G. Trigger (Ed.), ''Northeast'' (pp.&nbsp;160\u2013176). ''Handbook of North American Indian languages'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D.C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Simpson, J. A.; & Weiner, E. S. C. (1989). \"Mohican\", ''Oxford English Dictionary''. Oxford: Clarendon Press. (Online version).\n* Sturtevant, William C. (Ed.). (1978\u2013present). ''Handbook of North American Indians'' (Vol. 1\u201320). Washington, D. C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n* Trigger, Bruce G. (Ed.). (1978). ''Northeast'', ''Handbook of North American Indians'' (Vol. 15). Washington, D. C.: Smithsonian Institution.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mahican}}\n* [http://www.mohican.com/ Stockbridge-Munsee community]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120822023701/http://www.mohican-nsn.gov/Departments/Library-Museum/Mohican_History/origin-and-early.htm Mohican nation Stockbridge-Munsee band: Our history]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100111075910/http://wolfweb.unr.edu/homepage/shubinsk/mohican.html Mohican Indians]\n\n{{Capital District}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mohican}}\n[[Category:Algonquian peoples]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Shawano County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Stockbridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Native American tribes in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Algonquian ethnonyms]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of North America]]\n[[Category:People of New Netherland]]\n[[Category:American Indian reservations in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Native Americans in the American Revolution]]\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixISBN erroror other ISBN error usingAutoEd(or wrap invalid ISBN in template to show error message)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohicans"}
{"title_page": "Best alternative to a negotiated agreement", "text_new": "{{short description|In negotiations, the best alternative to no deal}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2013}}\nIn [[negotiation theory]], the '''best alternative to a negotiated agreement''' or '''BATNA''' (no deal option) refers to the most advantageous alternative course of action a party can take if negotiations fail and an agreement cannot be reached. The exact opposite of this option is the WATNA (worst alternative to a negotiated agreement). The BATNA could include diverse situations, such as suspension of negotiations, transition to another negotiating partner, appeal to the court's ruling, the execution of strikes, and the formation of other forms of alliances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dic.mk.co.kr/cp/pop/desc.php?from=B&to=C&page=0&so=all|title=::\uc99d\uad8c\uc6a9\uc5b4\uc0ac\uc804::|website=dic.mk.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> BATNA is the key focus and the driving force behind a successful negotiator.  A party should generally not accept a worse resolution than its BATNA.  Care should be taken, however, to ensure that deals are accurately valued, taking into account all considerations, such as relationship value, [[time value of money]] and the likelihood that the other party will live up to their side of the bargain. These other considerations are often difficult to value, since they are frequently based on uncertain or qualitative considerations, rather than easily measurable and quantifiable factors.\n\nOftentimes, it is even more difficult to determine the BATNA of the other party. However, the information is crucial as the BATNA determines the other side\u2019s negotiation power. Sometimes, conclusions can be drawn by determining his/her main interests and the negotiation itself can be used to verify or falsify the assumptions. If, for example, it is assumed that a very early delivery date is of key importance to the negotiating partner, deliberately setting a later delivery date can be proposed. If this late delivery date is decidedly rejected, the desired delivery date is likely to be of great importance.<ref>''Jung/Krebs'', p. 42.</ref>\n\n== BATNA based tactics ==\nBecause of the importance of the BATNA for the negotiation success, several tactics focus on weakening the opponent\u2019s BATNA. This may be achieved e.g. by striving for exclusive negotiations, delaying or accelerating the ongoing negotiations or limiting the negotiation partner to technical systems. If a negotiator is faced with such tactics it is his/her task to examine the possible consequences for the own BATNA and to prevent or counteract any deterioration of the own party\u2019s BATNA.<ref>''Jung/Krebs'', p. 143.</ref>\n\n== BATNA and the order of negotiations ==\nThe BATNA can also influence the order in which negotiations are taken up with potential contracting partners. Favourable is a sequential approach. Here one starts negotiations with the less favoured partners and proceed negotiations with the preferred option afterwards. In this way there is the BATNA of a contract with the less favoured partner.<ref>''Jung/Krebs'', p. 44.</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe BATNA is often seen by negotiators not as a safety net, but rather as a point of leverage in negotiations. Although a negotiator's alternative options should, in theory, be straightforward to evaluate, the effort to understand which alternative represents a party's BATNA is often not invested. Options need to be actual and actionable to be of value,<ref>[https://www.negotiations.com/articles/best-alternative/ Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>{{Third-party-inline|date=July 2013}} however, without the investment of time, options will frequently be included that fail on one of these criteria.<ref>[https://www.yarooms.com/blog/batnaman-wins Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement | YArooms]</ref> {{Citation needed|date=October 2007}} Most managers overestimate their BATNA whilst simultaneously investing too little time into researching their real options.{{Third-party-inline|date=February 2015}} This can result in poor or faulty decision making and negotiating. Negotiators also need to be aware of the other negotiator's BATNA and to identify how it compares to what they are offering.<ref>Negotiation, Readings, Exercises and Cases, Roy J. Lewicki{{Full citation needed|date=July 2013}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nSome people may adopt aggressive, coercive, threatening and/or deceptive techniques. This is known as a hard negotiation style;<ref name=\"Nolan-Haley\">{{cite book|last=Nolan-Haley|first=Jaqueline M|title=Alternative Dispute Resolution in a Nutshell|year=2001|publisher=Thomson West|isbn=978-0-314-18014-8 |pages=39\u201350}}</ref> a theoretical example of this is ''adversarial approach style negotiation''.<ref name=\"Nolan-Haley\" /> Others may employ a soft style, which is friendly, trusting, compromising, and conflict avoiding.<ref name=\"Fisher and Ury\" /> According to Fisher and Ury, when hard negotiators meet soft negotiators, the hard negotiators usually win their position, but at the cost of potentially damaging the long term relationship between the parties.\n\nAttractive alternatives are needed to develop a strong BATNA. In the best-selling book ''Getting to YES: Negotiating Agreement Without Giving In'', the authors give three suggestions of how to accomplish this:\n\n# Creating a list of actions one might take if no agreement is reached\n# Converting some of the more promising ideas and transforming them into tangible and partial alternatives\n# Selecting the alternative that sounds best\n\nIn negotiations involving different cultures, all parties need to account for cultural cognitive behaviors and should not let judgments and biases affect the negotiation. The individual should be separate from the objective.<ref name=\"Fisher and Ury\" />{{Page needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nThe purpose here, as [[Philip Gulliver]] mentions, is for negotiation parties to be aware.<ref name=Gulliver>{{cite book|last=Gulliver|first=P.H|authorlink=Philip Gulliver|title=Disputes and Negotiation: A Cross Culture Perspective|year=1979|publisher=Academic Press|pages=287}}</ref>\n\nPreparation at all levels, including prejudice-free thoughts, emotion-free behavior, bias-free behavior are helpful according to Morris and Gelfand.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Morris|first1=Michael W.|last2=Gelfand|first2=Michele J.|title=Cultural Differences and Cognitive Dynamics: Expanding the Cognitive Perspective on Negotiation|editor1-last=Gelfand|editor1-first=Michele J.|editor2-last=Brett|editor2-first=Jeanne M.|work=The Handbook of Negotiation and Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xsOfOIzoZigC&pg=PA45|year=2004|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-4586-4|pages=45\u201370}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBATNA was developed by negotiation researchers [[Roger Fisher (academic)|Roger Fisher]] and [[William Ury]] of the Harvard Program on Negotiation (PON), in their series of books on [[Principled negotiation]] that started with ''[[Getting to YES]]'', unwittingly duplicating the [[game theory]] concept of a disagreement point from [[bargaining problem]]s pioneered by [[Nobel Laureate]] [[John Forbes Nash]] decades earlier.<ref name=\"Fisher and Ury\">{{cite book|last=Fisher and Ury|first=Roger and William|title=Getting to YES|year=2011|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-311875-6|pages=1\u2013170}}</ref><ref name=\"Myerson\">{{cite web|last=Myerson|first=Roger B|title=Nash Equilibrium and the History of Economic Theory|url=http://home.uchicago.edu/rmyerson/research/jelnash.pdf|publisher=Journal of Economic Literature|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref> A [[Nash Equilibrium]] is reached among a group of players when no player can benefit from changing strategies if every other player sticks to their current strategy.<ref name=\"Hawkins and Steiner\">{{cite web|last=Hawkins and Steiner |first=Jeff and Neil |title=The Nash Equilibrium Meets Batna |url=http://www.hnlr.org/print/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/257-264.pdf |work=Gamed Therory Varied Uses in ADR |publisher=Harvard University Press |accessdate=1 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228140045/http://www.hnlr.org/print/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/257-264.pdf |archivedate=28 February 2013 }}</ref> For example, Amy and Phil are in Nash Equilibrium if Amy is making the best decision she can, taking into account Phil's decision, and Phil is making the best decision he can, taking into account Amy's decision. Likewise, a group of players are in Nash Equilibrium if each one is making the best decision that he or she can, taking into account the decisions of the others.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Conflict resolution research]]\n* [[Getting to Yes]]\n* [[Opportunity cost]]\n* [[Zone of possible agreement]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.negotiationtraining.com.au/articles/next-best-option/ BATNA Explained by Dr David Venter]\n* Alternative [https://www.negotiations.com/definition/batna/ definition of BATNA]\n* [https://www.negotiations.com/articles/best-alternative/ BATNA Explained] by Negotiation Experts\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n\n[[Category:Negotiation]]\n[[Category:Dispute resolution]]\n[[Category:Business terms]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|In negotiations, the best alternative to no deal}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2013}}\nIn [[negotiation theory]], the '''best alternative to a negotiated agreement''' or '''BATNA''' (no deal option) refers to the most advantageous alternative course of action a party can take if negotiations fail and an agreement cannot be reached. The exact opposite of this option is the WATNA (worst alternative to a negotiated agreement). The BATNA could include diverse situations, such as suspension of negotiations, transition to another negotiating partner, appeal to the court's ruling, the execution of strikes, and the formation of other forms of alliances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dic.mk.co.kr/cp/pop/desc.php?from=B&to=C&page=0&so=all|title=::\uc99d\uad8c\uc6a9\uc5b4\uc0ac\uc804::|website=dic.mk.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> BATNA is the key focus and the driving force behind a successful negotiator.  A party should generally not accept a worse resolution than its BATNA.  Care should be taken, however, to ensure that deals are accurately valued, taking into account all considerations, such as relationship value, [[time value of money]] and the likelihood that the other party will live up to their side of the bargain. These other considerations are often difficult to value, since they are frequently based on uncertain or qualitative considerations, rather than easily measurable and quantifiable factors.\n\nOftentimes, it is even more difficult to determine the BATNA of the other party. However, the information is crucial as the BATNA determines the other side\u2019s negotiation power. Sometimes, conclusions can be drawn by determining his/her main interests and the negotiation itself can be used to verify or falsify the assumptions. If, for example, it is assumed that a very early delivery date is of key importance to the negotiating partner, deliberately setting a later delivery date can be proposed. If this late delivery date is decidedly rejected, the desired delivery date is likely to be of great importance.<ref>''Jung/Krebs'', p. 42.</ref>\n\n== BATNA based tactics ==\nBecause of the importance of the BATNA for the negotiation success, several tactics focus on weakening the opponent\u2019s BATNA. This may be achieved e.g. by striving for exclusive negotiations, delaying or accelerating the ongoing negotiations or limiting the negotiation partner to technical systems. If a negotiator is faced with such tactics it is his/her task to examine the possible consequences for the own BATNA and to prevent or counteract any deterioration of the own partys\u2019 BATNA.<ref>''Jung/Krebs'', p. 143.</ref>\n\n== BATNA and the order of negotiations ==\nThe BATNA can also influence the order in which negotiations are taken up with potential contracting partners. Favourable is a sequential approach. Here one starts negotiations with the less favoured partners and proceed negotiations with the preferred option afterwards. In this way there is the BATNA of a contract with the less favoured partner.<ref>''Jung/Krebs'', p. 44.</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe BATNA is often seen by negotiators not as a safety net, but rather as a point of leverage in negotiations. Although a negotiator's alternative options should, in theory, be straightforward to evaluate, the effort to understand which alternative represents a party's BATNA is often not invested. Options need to be actual and actionable to be of value,<ref>[https://www.negotiations.com/articles/best-alternative/ Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>{{Third-party-inline|date=July 2013}} however, without the investment of time, options will frequently be included that fail on one of these criteria.<ref>[https://www.yarooms.com/blog/batnaman-wins Best Alternative to a Negotiated Agreement | YArooms]</ref> {{Citation needed|date=October 2007}} Most managers overestimate their BATNA whilst simultaneously investing too little time into researching their real options.{{Third-party-inline|date=February 2015}} This can result in poor or faulty decision making and negotiating. Negotiators also need to be aware of the other negotiator's BATNA and to identify how it compares to what they are offering.<ref>Negotiation, Readings, Exercises and Cases, Roy J. Lewicki{{Full citation needed|date=July 2013}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nSome people may adopt aggressive, coercive, threatening and/or deceptive techniques. This is known as a hard negotiation style;<ref name=\"Nolan-Haley\">{{cite book|last=Nolan-Haley|first=Jaqueline M|title=Alternative Dispute Resolution in a Nutshell|year=2001|publisher=Thomson West|isbn=978-0-314-18014-8 |pages=39\u201350}}</ref> a theoretical example of this is ''adversarial approach style negotiation''.<ref name=\"Nolan-Haley\" /> Others may employ a soft style, which is friendly, trusting, compromising, and conflict avoiding.<ref name=\"Fisher and Ury\" /> According to Fisher and Ury, when hard negotiators meet soft negotiators, the hard negotiators usually win their position, but at the cost of potentially damaging the long term relationship between the parties.\n\nAttractive alternatives are needed to develop a strong BATNA. In the best-selling book ''Getting to YES: Negotiating Agreement Without Giving In'', the authors give three suggestions of how to accomplish this:\n\n# Creating a list of actions one might take if no agreement is reached\n# Converting some of the more promising ideas and transforming them into tangible and partial alternatives\n# Selecting the alternative that sounds best\n\nIn negotiations involving different cultures, all parties need to account for cultural cognitive behaviors and should not let judgments and biases affect the negotiation. The individual should be separate from the objective.<ref name=\"Fisher and Ury\" />{{Page needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nThe purpose here, as [[Philip Gulliver]] mentions, is for negotiation parties to be aware.<ref name=Gulliver>{{cite book|last=Gulliver|first=P.H|authorlink=Philip Gulliver|title=Disputes and Negotiation: A Cross Culture Perspective|year=1979|publisher=Academic Press|pages=287}}</ref>\n\nPreparation at all levels, including prejudice-free thoughts, emotion-free behavior, bias-free behavior are helpful according to Morris and Gelfand.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Morris|first1=Michael W.|last2=Gelfand|first2=Michele J.|title=Cultural Differences and Cognitive Dynamics: Expanding the Cognitive Perspective on Negotiation|editor1-last=Gelfand|editor1-first=Michele J.|editor2-last=Brett|editor2-first=Jeanne M.|work=The Handbook of Negotiation and Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xsOfOIzoZigC&pg=PA45|year=2004|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-4586-4|pages=45\u201370}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBATNA was developed by negotiation researchers [[Roger Fisher (academic)|Roger Fisher]] and [[William Ury]] of the Harvard Program on Negotiation (PON), in their series of books on [[Principled negotiation]] that started with ''[[Getting to YES]]'', unwittingly duplicating the [[game theory]] concept of a disagreement point from [[bargaining problem]]s pioneered by [[Nobel Laureate]] [[John Forbes Nash]] decades earlier.<ref name=\"Fisher and Ury\">{{cite book|last=Fisher and Ury|first=Roger and William|title=Getting to YES|year=2011|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-311875-6|pages=1\u2013170}}</ref><ref name=\"Myerson\">{{cite web|last=Myerson|first=Roger B|title=Nash Equilibrium and the History of Economic Theory|url=http://home.uchicago.edu/rmyerson/research/jelnash.pdf|publisher=Journal of Economic Literature|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref> A [[Nash Equilibrium]] is reached among a group of players when no player can benefit from changing strategies if every other player sticks to their current strategy.<ref name=\"Hawkins and Steiner\">{{cite web|last=Hawkins and Steiner |first=Jeff and Neil |title=The Nash Equilibrium Meets Batna |url=http://www.hnlr.org/print/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/257-264.pdf |work=Gamed Therory Varied Uses in ADR |publisher=Harvard University Press |accessdate=1 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228140045/http://www.hnlr.org/print/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/257-264.pdf |archivedate=28 February 2013 }}</ref> For example, Amy and Phil are in Nash Equilibrium if Amy is making the best decision she can, taking into account Phil's decision, and Phil is making the best decision he can, taking into account Amy's decision. Likewise, a group of players are in Nash Equilibrium if each one is making the best decision that he or she can, taking into account the decisions of the others.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Conflict resolution research]]\n* [[Getting to Yes]]\n* [[Opportunity cost]]\n* [[Zone of possible agreement]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.negotiationtraining.com.au/articles/next-best-option/ BATNA Explained by Dr David Venter]\n* Alternative [https://www.negotiations.com/definition/batna/ definition of BATNA]\n* [https://www.negotiations.com/articles/best-alternative/ BATNA Explained] by Negotiation Experts\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n\n[[Category:Negotiation]]\n[[Category:Dispute resolution]]\n[[Category:Business terms]]\n", "name_user": "RafDouglas", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Best_alternative_to_a_negotiated_agreement"}
{"title_page": "List of American cheeses", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{multiple issues|\n {{refimprove|date=January 2010}}\n {{List missing criteria|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Brickcheese.jpg|thumb|right|A package of [[brick cheese]]]]\n\nThis is a [[list of cheeses]] typical of the United States. Types of cheese are included; [[brand name]]s are only included if they apply to a distinct variety of cheese.  Many additional European-type cheeses are also made in the United States, such as [[Brie]], [[Cheddar cheese|Cheddar]], [[Gouda (cheese)|Gouda]], [[mozzarella]] and [[provolone]]. Also, many local dairies throughout the country produce [[artisan cheese]]s and other more localized flavors.  (The term \"American cheese\" is also sometimes misunderstood outside the United States to refer to [[processed cheese|processed cheese products]].)  Many American cheese varieties are related to European cheeses, with slightly different recipes, and with European-sounding names, such as [[Swiss cheese (North America)|Swiss cheese]], which is not normally found or produced in Switzerland.  Almost half of the cheese produced in the United States comes from Wisconsin and California.<ref name=\"usproduction\"/>\n\n==American cream cheeses==\n[[File:Bergenost_Cheese_93_bg_122306.jpg|thumb|[[Bergenost]] cheese]]\n* [[Bergenost]]\n* [[Cream cheese]]\n* [[Creole cream cheese]]\n* [[Cup cheese]]\n* [[Red Hawk cheese]], triple-cr\u00e8me cow's milk cheese with a brine washed rind, made in California\n* [[Kunik cheese]]\n\n==American soft cheeses==\n* [[Brick cheese]]\n* [[Cheese curd]]\n* [[Colby cheese]]\n* [[Colby-Jack cheese]]\n* [[Farmer cheese]]\n** [[Hoop cheese]], drier version of farmer cheese\n* [[String cheese]], particular American variety of mozzarella with a stringy texture\n* [[Cougar Gold cheese]], An American cheddar\n* [[Humboldt Fog]], made in California\n* [[Liederkranz cheese]]\n* [[Monterey Jack]]\n** [[Pepper jack cheese]], variety of Monterey Jack\n* [[Pinconning cheese]], aged variety of Colby\n* [[Muenster cheese]], extremely mild, semi-soft with annatto exterior, nothing like name-controlled washed rind Alsacian Muenster\n* [[Swiss cheese (North America)|Swiss cheese]]\n* [[Teleme cheese]]\n* [[Vermont cheddar]]\n\n==American hard cheeses==\n* [[Capricious (cheese)|Capricious]], goat's milk cheese made in [[Petaluma, California]]\n* [[Parmigiano-Reggiano#American generic parmesan cheese|American generic parmesan]], developed in the United States but inspired by [[Parmigiano-Reggiano]] cheese from Italy\n\n==American blue cheeses==\n* [[Maytag Blue cheese]], brand name which is also a distinct variety of cheese\n\n==Processed cheeses==\n* [[American cheese]], a variety of processed cheese usually created from a combination of Colby and Cheddar cheeses\n* [[Government cheese]], variety of processed cheese food\n* [[Nacho cheese]]\n* [[Pimento cheese]]\n* [[Provel cheese]]\n* [[Velveeta]], brand name for a softer style of processed cheese than American cheese\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food|United States|Lists}}\n* [[List of cheeses]]\n* [[List of cheesemakers]]\n* [[List of American foods]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"usproduction\">{{cite web|accessdate=2010-12-21 |publisher=ICAR |title=U.S. milk and dairy product production |url=http://www.2008icar.org/about_us_milk.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724203322/http://www.2008icar.org/about_us_milk.asp |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{American cheeses}}\n{{Cuisine of the United States}}\n{{Cheese}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:American cheeses}}\n[[Category:American cheeses|*]]\n[[Category:American cuisine-related lists|Cheeses (American)]]\n[[Category:Lists of cheeses|American]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{multiple issues|\n {{refimprove|date=January 2010}}\n {{List missing criteria|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Brickcheese.jpg|thumb|right|A package of [[brick cheese]]]]\n\nThis is a [[list of cheeses]] typical of the United States. Types of cheese are included; [[brand name]]s are only included if they apply to a distinct variety of cheese.  Many additional European-type cheeses are also made in the United States, such as [[Brie]], [[Cheddar cheese|Cheddar]], [[Gouda (cheese)|Gouda]], [[mozzarella]] and [[provolone]]. Also, many local dairies throughout the country produce [[artisan cheese]]s and other more localized flavors.  (The term \"American cheese\" is also sometimes misunderstood outside the United States to refer to [[processed cheese|processed cheese products]].)  Many American cheese varieties are related to European cheeses, with slightly different recipes, and with European-sounding names, such as [[Swiss cheese]], which is not normally found or produced in Switzerland.  Almost half of the cheese produced in the United States comes from Wisconsin and California.<ref name=\"usproduction\"/>\n\n==American cream cheeses==\n[[File:Bergenost_Cheese_93_bg_122306.jpg|thumb|[[Bergenost]] cheese]]\n* [[Bergenost]]\n* [[Cream cheese]]\n* [[Creole cream cheese]]\n* [[Cup cheese]]\n* [[Red Hawk cheese]], triple-cr\u00e8me cow's milk cheese with a brine washed rind, made in California\n* [[Kunik cheese]]\n\n==American soft cheeses==\n* [[Brick cheese]]\n* [[Cheese curd]]\n* [[Colby cheese]]\n* [[Colby-Jack cheese]]\n* [[Farmer cheese]]\n** [[Hoop cheese]], drier version of farmer cheese\n* [[String cheese]], particular American variety of mozzarella with a stringy texture\n* [[Cougar Gold cheese]], An American cheddar\n* [[Humboldt Fog]], made in California\n* [[Liederkranz cheese]]\n* [[Monterey Jack]]\n** [[Pepper jack cheese]], variety of Monterey Jack\n* [[Pinconning cheese]], aged variety of Colby\n* [[Muenster cheese]], extremely mild, semi-soft with annatto exterior, nothing like name-controlled washed rind Alsacian Muenster\n* [[Swiss cheese]]\n* [[Teleme cheese]]\n* [[Vermont cheddar]]\n\n==American hard cheeses==\n* [[Capricious (cheese)|Capricious]], goat's milk cheese made in [[Petaluma, California]]\n* [[Parmigiano-Reggiano#American generic parmesan cheese|American generic parmesan]], developed in the United States but inspired by [[Parmigiano-Reggiano]] cheese from Italy\n\n==American blue cheeses==\n* [[Maytag Blue cheese]], brand name which is also a distinct variety of cheese\n\n==Processed cheeses==\n* [[American cheese]], a variety of processed cheese usually created from a combination of Colby and Cheddar cheeses\n* [[Government cheese]], variety of processed cheese food\n* [[Nacho cheese]]\n* [[Pimento cheese]]\n* [[Provel cheese]]\n* [[Velveeta]], brand name for a softer style of processed cheese than American cheese\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food|United States|Lists}}\n* [[List of cheeses]]\n* [[List of cheesemakers]]\n* [[List of American foods]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"usproduction\">{{cite web|accessdate=2010-12-21 |publisher=ICAR |title=U.S. milk and dairy product production |url=http://www.2008icar.org/about_us_milk.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724203322/http://www.2008icar.org/about_us_milk.asp |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{American cheeses}}\n{{Cuisine of the United States}}\n{{Cheese}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:American cheeses}}\n[[Category:American cheeses|*]]\n[[Category:American cuisine-related lists|Cheeses (American)]]\n[[Category:Lists of cheeses|American]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSwiss cheese(link changed toSwiss cheese (North America); link changed toSwiss cheese (North America)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_American_cheeses"}
{"title_page": "Hay Dale", "text_new": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Hay Dale|map_alt=|photo=Hay Dale on Limestone Way.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=Hay Dale on the Limestone Way|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2902|-1.8207|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|elevation_ref=|direction=North-South|length={{Convert|0.75|mi|0}}|width={{Convert|120|m|0}}|area=|depth={{Convert|30|m|0}}|type=|elevation_m=|boundaries=|topo=|towns=|traversed=|watercourses=|footnotes=|embed=}}\n[[File:Hay Dale Nature Reserve Sign.jpg|thumb|290x290px|Hay Dale Nature Reserve]]\n'''Hay Dale''' is a short dry valley near [[Buxton]], [[Derbyshire]], in the [[Peak District]] of England. There is a farmland plateau on either side. The foot of the valley leads into [[Peter Dale (Derbyshire)|Peter Dale]] to the south at Dale Head and on into [[Monk's Dale]].<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nHay Dale is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]]. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] ([[Lathkill Dale]], [[Cressbrook Dale]], Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk's Dale]]). The [[Carboniferous Limestone|Carboniferous limestone]] rocks of the reserve were formed 350 million years ago from the shells and sediments of a tropical sea. The landscape was then sculpted by the ice sheets from the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] 20,000 years ago. The reserve contains ash woodland, limestone grassland and many wildflowers including [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]], [[Primula veris|cowslip]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock rose]] and [[Thymelaeaceae|thyme]]. Butterfies are abundant and include the [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]].<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Early Purple Orchid in Hay Dale.jpg|thumb|290x290px|Early Purple Orchid in Hay Dale]]\nThe [[Limestone Way]] and the [[Peak District Boundary Walk]] long-distance footpaths run along the length of the gentle valley floor. The [[Pennine Bridleway]] crosses the northern end of the dale. Where the Limestone Way crosses the A623 road (about 1&nbsp;km north of Hay Dale), the route of the old [[Batham Gate]] [[Roman roads|Roman road]] runs east\u2013west.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\nAccess into Haydale from the South can be made from the village of Wormhill along the Pennine Bridleway and through Peter Dale. From the North there is a footpath from the village of Peak Forest (on the A623 road) through Dam Dale.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\n\n{{Infobox valley|name=Hay Dale|map_alt=|photo=Hay Dale on Limestone Way.jpg|photo_size=|photo_alt=|photo_caption=Hay Dale on the Limestone Way|map_image=|map_size=|elevation=|map_caption=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|relief=|label=|label_position=|coordinates={{Coord|53.2902|-1.8207|display=title, inline|type:valley}}|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|elevation_ref=|direction=North-South|length={{Convert|0.75|mi|0}}|width={{Convert|120|m|0}}|area=|depth={{Convert|30|m|0}}|type=|elevation_m=|boundaries=|topo=|towns=|traversed=|watercourses=|footnotes=|embed=}}\n[[File:Hay Dale Nature Reserve Sign.jpg|thumb|290x290px|Hay Dale Nature Reserve]]\n'''Hay Dale''' is a short dry valley near [[Buxton]], [[Derbyshire]], in the [[Peak District]] of England. There is a farmland plateau on either side. The foot of the valley leads into [[Peter Dale (Derbyshire)|Peter Dale]] to the south at Dale Head and on into [[Monk's Dale]].<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nHay Dale is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]]. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] ([[Lathkill Dale]], [[Cressbrook Dale]], Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk's Dale]]). The [[Carboniferous Limestone|Carboniferous limestone]] rocks of the reserve were formed 350 million years ago from the shells and sediments of a tropical sea. The landscape was then sculpted by the ice sheets from the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] 20,000 years ago. The reserve contains ash woodland, limestone grassland and many wildflowers including [[Orchis mascula|early purple orchid]], [[Primula veris|cowslip]], [[Helianthemum nummularium|common rock rose]] and [[Thymelaeaceae|thyme]]. Butterfies are abundant and include the [[Aricia agestis|brown argus]].<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Limestone Way]] and the [[Peak District Boundary Walk]] long-distance footpaths run along the length of the gentle valley floor. The [[Pennine Bridleway]] crosses the northern end of the dale. Where the Limestone Way crosses the A623 road (about 1&nbsp;km north of Hay Dale), the route of the old [[Batham Gate]] [[Roman roads|Roman road]] runs east\u2013west.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\nAccess into Haydale from the South can be made from the village of Wormhill along the Pennine Bridleway and through Peter Dale. From the North there is a footpath from the village of Peak Forest (on the A623 road) through Dam Dale.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Photo of orchid", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hay_Dale"}
{"title_page": "Idiot Wind", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|the Swedish artist|Amanda Bergman}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Idiot Wind\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blood on the Tracks]]\n| released = January 1975\n| recorded = 27 December 1974\n| studio   = [[Sound 80]],<br>[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\n| venue    = \n| genre    = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length   = 7:48\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| tracks   = {{Blood on the Tracks tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Idiot Wind'''\" is a song by [[Bob Dylan]], which appeared on his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.  The song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year. Dylan recorded the song in September 1974, but as with some other songs from ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'', re-recorded it in December 1974. Between the recordings, he often reworked the lyrics. A live version of the song was released on Dylan's 1976 album ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'', and all of the studio outtakes from the September sessions were released on the deluxe edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' in 2018.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nThe song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year and a separation from Sara Lowndes, who he had married in 1965. Dylan had moved to a farm in Minnesota with his brother, David Zimmerman and there started to write the songs that were recorded for his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.<ref name=\"UNCUT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656/ |title=Shelter From The Storm \u2013 the inside story of Bob Dylan's Blood on the Tracks |last=Hasted |first=Nick |date=15 November 2013 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011356/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the Spring of 1974, Dylan had taken art classes at [[Carnegie Hall]] and was influenced by his tutor [[Norman Raeben]].<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Rogovoy2009\">{{cite book|author=Seth Rogovoy|title=Bob Dylan: Prophet, Mystic, Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdbgeObYgIkC&pg=PA160|date=24 November 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-5983-2|pages=160\u2013}}</ref> and, in particular, Raeben's view of [[time]].<ref name=\"GillOdegard2004\">{{cite book|author1=Andy Gill|author2=Kevin Odegard|title=A Simple Twist of Fate: Bob Dylan and the Making of Blood on the Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tt0HAQAAMAAJ|date=January 2004|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-81231-6}}</ref> Dylan was later to say that Idiot Wind was \"a song I wanted to make as a painting.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\">{{cite book|author=Bill Flanagan|title=Written in My Soul: Conversations with Rock's Great Songwriters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|date=1 April 2010|publisher=RosettaBooks|isbn=978-0-7953-1081-2|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506011534/https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Idiot Wind\" was a derogatory phrase employed by Raeben and this may have inspired Dylan's use of it, although the term also appears in the poem \"June 1940\" by [[Weldon Kees]] and that may have been the reference point.<ref name=\"Wilentz2011\">{{cite book|author=Sean Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sb5UygkZlH0C&pg=PA140|date=15 February 2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4070-7411-5|pages=140\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDylan first recorded \"Idiot Wind\" in New York City on 12 September 1974 during the initial ''Blood on the Tracks'' sessions at [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]]. The first recording included just guitar and bass, with organ later [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]]. That December, working from a suggestion from his brother that the album should have a more commercial sound, Dylan re-recorded half the songs on ''Blood on the Tracks'', including \"Idiot Wind\", in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /><ref name=\"OHAGAN\">{{cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Sean |title=The raw, painful birth of Blood on the Tracks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417055617/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks Review |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |work=BBC |year=2007 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919065715/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |archive-date=19 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Creswell2007\">{{cite book|author=Toby Creswell|title=1001 Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bhYnNaM0zEUC&pg=PA24|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing|isbn=1-74273-148-1|pages=24\u2013}}</ref> The New York sessions were engineered by [[Phil Ramone]]. In New York, Dylan's guitar was tuned to [[Open D tuning|open D]] with a [[capo]] on the second [[fret]] so that all of the songs were in the [[Key (music)|key]] of E.<ref name=\"Wise2017\">{{cite book|author=Wise Publications|title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEejDgAAQBAJ|date=8 April 2017|publisher=Wise Publications|isbn=978-1-78323-916-0}}</ref> Paul Martinson was the engineer for the Minneapolis sessions.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" />\n\nThe re-recorded versions were radical departures from the original recordings, and each new recording included changes to the lyrics from the earlier versions.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /><ref name=\"Dalton2012\">{{cite book|author=David Dalton|title=Who Is That Man? In Search of the Real Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SDcDAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT346|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-779-2|pages=346\u2013}}</ref> The September 1974 recording of Idiot Wind featured just acoustic guitar and bass instrumentation, whereas the re-recording made on 27 December 1974 and issued on ''Blood on the Tracks'', featured a full band. This group of local musicians had been hurriedly been put together, and Dylan had not previously met them.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"AMSO\" /> The Minneapolis recordings are in [[standard tuning]].<ref name=\"Wise2017\" /> [[Clinton Heylin]] recounts that Dylan frequently reworked the song from September to December.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Still on the Road: The Songs of Bob Dylan Vol. 2 1974-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaSeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84901-494-6|pages=55\u2013}}</ref> In a 1991 interview with [[Paul Zollo]], Dylan said that there could be many more verses for the song and that it could be constantly reworked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn\u2019t stop. It wouldn\u2019t stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It\u2019s something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref> Zollo contrasts the ''Blood on the Tracks'' version with the one from ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' which was Take 4, with added organ overdubs, recorded on 19 September 1974 in New York, and opines that the gentler delivery of the song in the September version \"makes the inherent disquiet of the song even more disturbing.\"<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\" /><ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |title=Read the complete tracklisting for Bob Dylan\u2019s More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=20 September 2018 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBarbara O'Dair (2009) links the song to two of Dylan's other compositions, \"Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands\" (1966) and \"Sara\" (1976) as a set of songs written across ten years \"addressing a woman that bears a resemblance to his now ex-wife Sara Lowndes.\" O'Dair criticises the song for [[victim blaming]].<ref name=\"ODAIR2009\">{{cite book |last=O'Dair |first=Barbara |editor-last1=Dettmar |editor-first1=Kevin |title=The Cambridge Companion to Bob Dylan |page= 83 |chapter=Bob Dylan and gender politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73eAjOofhCAC|date=19 February 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82843-7}}</ref> avid Goldblatt and Edward Necarsulmer (2011) say that in the song, Dylan \"explores the bitterness of resentment and revenge against a lover and against one's own love who botched their love.\"<ref name=\"PVI2011\">{{cite book |last1=Goldblatt |first1=David |last2=Necarsulmer IV |first2=Edward |editor-last1=Porter |editor-first1=Carl J. |editor-last2=Vernezze |editor-first2=Peter |editor-last3=Irwin |editor-first3=William |title=Bob Dylan and Philosophy: It's Alright Ma (I'm Only Thinking) |publisher=Open Court |date=2011 |page=163 |chapter=Language on the Lam(b): Tarantula in Dylan and Nietzsche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JaOqtb977hQC |isbn=978-0-8126-9760-5 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> Dylan has denied that the song is personal, stating in 1985 that:<ref name=\"WILLMAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |title=Dylan's blood-best album: 40 facts about the 40-year-old Blood On The Tracks |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=21 January 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405155031/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I thought I might have gone a little bit too far with 'Idiot Wind'\u2026 I didn't really think I was giving away too much; I thought that it seemed so personal that people would think it was about so-and-so who was close to me. It wasn't \u2026 I didn't feel that one was too personal, but I felt it seemed too personal. Which might be the same thing, I don't know.\"}}\n\nTimothy Hampton takes the song as political, and a commentary on the [[Vietnam War]],<ref name=\"Hampton2019\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Hampton|title=Bob Dylan's Poetics: How the Songs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51WRDwAAQBAJ|date=26 March 2019|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-1-942130-15-4}}</ref> whereas David Dalton feels that Dylan draws parallels between his personal situation and the national one, and \"turns his own fate into an allegory of the soured American dream.\"<ref name=\"Dalton2012\" />\n\nDylan and Lowndes' relationship deteriorated in 1976, and David Kinney relates how Dylan played Idiot Wind in a 1976 show at Fort Collins whilst Lowndes was in the audience, noting in the following sentence that the pair were divorced the following year.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" /> \n\nIndividual outtakes from the New York sessions were released in 1991 on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' and in 2018 on the single-CD and 2-LP versions of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', while the complete New York sessions were released on the deluxe edition of the latter album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The deluxe version of  ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'' also included a remix of the December 1974 master issued on ''Blood on the Tracks''.<ref name=\"MBMTREL\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''.<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album ''Blood on the Tracks'' received mixed reviews on release.<ref name=\"Williamson2004\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Williamson|title=The Rough Guide to Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R2c8AQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-139-5}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' carried two reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/10-classic-albums-rolling-stone-originally-panned-101316/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-1975-101880/ |title=10 Classic Albums Rolling Stone Originally Panned  |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=25 July 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jonathan Cott described the album as \"magnificent and memorable\" and Idiot Wind, which he saw as equally as accomplished as the other songs, as \"explosive and bitter.\" Cott observed that it was the first time that Dylan had included himself in a condemnation in one of his songs, with the line \"We\u2019re idiots, babe/It's a wonder we can even feed ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-55031/  |title=Bob Dylan: Blood on the Tracks  |last=Cott |first=Jonathan |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, in the other ''Rolling Stone'' review, [[Jon Landau]] disparaged \"the childishness (without any redeeming childlike wonder) of so much of Idiot Wind.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |title=Blood on the Tracks |last=Landau |first=Jon |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230122112/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lester Bangs]] originally regarded the song as \"absurdly spiteful\" and was unimpressed, although he soon found himself listening to the album frequently.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2003 book ''[[Dylan's Visions of Sin]]'', [[Christopher Ricks|Professor Christopher Ricks]] discusses a particular lyrical couplet from the song, namely: \"Blowing like a circle around my skull/From the [[Grand Coulee Dam]] to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]].\" Ricks praises this as \"fierce \u2026 And it's a true rhyme because of the metaphorical relation, because of what a head of state is, and the body politic, and because of the relation of the Capitol to the skull (another of those white domes), with which it disconcertingly rhymes. An imperfect rhyme, perfectly judged.\"<ref name=\"Ricks2011\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlDWua9p8lEC|date=5 May 2011|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-0-85786-202-0}}</ref> The same rhyme had impressed [[Allen Ginsberg]], who wrote to Dylan comparing it to an image from [[The Bridge (long poem)|The Bridge]] by [[Hart Crane]]. Dylan was apparently gratified to receive Ginsberg's letter, and it was a contributing factor in leading to Ginsberg being invited onto the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/on-the-road-with-bob-dylan-joan-baez-and-the-rolling-thunder-revue-183508/ |title=On the Road With Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the Rolling Thunder Revue  |last=Hentoff |first=Nat |date=15 January 1976 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In his 1976 review in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Paul Cowan also referred to these lyrics, saying that they evoked both [[Woody Guthrie]] in the language used and [[T.S. Elliot]] in the delivery of the vocal. Like Cott, Cowan noted the ultimately self-accusatory nature of the lyrics, which he felt provided a surprising conclusion to the song.<ref name=\"COWAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |title=Riffs: Bob Dylan\u2019s Pain \u2014 Flip Side of Cruelty |last=Cowan |first=Paul |date=3 February 1975 |work=The Village Voice |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316142900/https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lyrics referencing the Capitol replaced the earlier \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your jaw/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the [[Mardi Gras]]\" used in New York.<ref name=\"Burger2018\">{{cite book|author=Jeff Burger|title=Dylan on Dylan: Interviews and Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT257|date=1 May 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-0-912777-44-3|pages=257\u2013}}</ref> Zollo also felt that this pair of lines was the highlight of the song.<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\">{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn\u2019t stop. It wouldn\u2019t stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It\u2019s something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[1001 Songs]]'', [[Toby Creswell]] says that the track is an \"epic of elegantly phrased bile\" and is \"not based on logical exposition.\"<ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /> The song was 16th on '' [[American Songwriter]]'' magazine's 2009 ranking of ''The 30 Greatest Dylan Songs''.<ref name=\"AMSO\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-16-idiot-wind/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #16, \"Idiot Wind\"|author=Schlansky, Evan|date=20 April 2009|publisher=americansongwriter.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and placed fourth in Jim Beviglia's 2013 book ''Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs''.<ref name=\"Beviglia2013\">{{cite book|author=Jim Beviglia|title=Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRMeAAAAQBAJ|date=11 July 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8824-1}}</ref>\n\nWhen Dylan won the [[Nobel prize for literature]] in 2016, ''[[The Guardian]]'' cited \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your teeth/ You\u2019re an idiot, babe/ It's a wonder that you still know how to breathe\" from Idiot Wind as one of his greatest lyrics.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Are these the lyrics that won Bob Dylan a Nobel prize? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521040933/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |archive-date=21 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', Sean O'Hagan remarked of the song \"By turns paranoid, derisory and vengeful, it is a dark masterpiece of venomous intent, a great part of its raw power resting in the very discomfort the listener feels as it gathers momentum and the tone becomes ever more bitter.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Live Performances==\nDylan played the song live 55 times between 18 April 1976, when it was first included in his set, at Civic Centre, Lakeland, Florida; and 30 August 1992 when he played it at the Orpheum Theatre, Minneapolis. 1976 and 1992 were the only years in which it featured in his live shows. As of April 2020, he has not performed it live since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Clinton Heylin]], a prolific author of material about Dylan, flew from England to California to attend Dylan's shows when he heard that Idiot Wind was being played live again.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nArtist Mohammad Omer Khalil produced a series of etchings, inspired by Dylan's music, that were displayed at the [[National Museum of African Art]] in 1994, including one entitled Idiot Wind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africa.si.edu/collections/view/objects/asitem/People@120/2?t:state:flow=847c62c4-c3b4-469a-baaf-52952b9c28ed |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=africa.si.edu |publisher=National Museum of African Art |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of the lyrics of Idiot Wind are mentioned in the 1995 song \"[[Only Wanna Be with You]]\" by American band [[Hootie & the Blowfish]]. The use of Dylan's lyrics reportedly led to an out-of-court settlement, with Dylan receiving money from Hootie & the Blowfish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|title=Darius Rucker on 'Wagon Wheel' and the Future of Hootie|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=19 July 2013|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023200015/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSwedish musician [[Amanda Bergman]] used to perform under the stage name ''Idiot Wind''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|title = The shark that became Jaw Lesson is now Idiot Wind|date = 13 September 2010|website = svt.se|publisher = Swedish Television|last = Beckman|first = Eva|language = Swedish|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426205311/http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|archivedate = 26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a question on the \"Ask Lou\" section of his website in 2007, singer-songwriter [[Lou Reed]] cited \"Idiot Wind\" as the song he wished he had written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |work=loureed.com |title=Ask Lou |date=December 2007 |access-date=12 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415130637/http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |archive-date=15 April 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Novelist [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] included Idiot Wind as one of his eight records for [[Desert Island Discs]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |title=Peter Carey |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 2008 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in the play ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]''. In the original London production, it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Richard |title=Girl from the North Country lets us hear Bob Dylan's mysteries anew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 January 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150058/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> who won the 2018 Laurence Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Musical for her role.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Olivier Awards 2018: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930235126/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |archive-date=30 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nPeter Kaldheim's 2019 novel ''Idiot Wind: A Memoir'' was published by Canongate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|title=Idiot Wind by Peter Kaldheim \u2013 Canongate Books|website=canongate.co.uk|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715152051/https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |title=In Idiot Wind, a Lost Soul Finds His Way Home |last=Williams |first=John |date=28 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729233051/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |archive-date=29 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\nThe officially released versions of the song on Bob Dylan albums are below.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" /><ref name=\"MBMTREL\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |title=1976 soon to be divorced |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |title=Still on the road: 1976 Rolling Thunder Revue II |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  !! Album !! Release Year !! Recorded at !! Recording date !! [[Take]] !! Personnel !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || ''[[Blood On The Tracks]]'' || 1975 || [[Sound 80]] || 27/12/1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums ||\n|-\n| 2 || ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'' || 1976 || [[Sonny Lubick Field at Hughes Stadium|Hughes Stadium]] || 23/05/1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, [[Scarlet Rivera]]: violin; [[T Bone Burnett|T-bone J. Henry Burnett]]: guitar, piano; [[Steven Soles]]: guitar; [[Mick Ronson]]: guitar; [[Bob Neuwirth|Bobby Neuwirth]]: guitar, vocals; [[Roger McGuinn]]: guitar, vocals; [[David Mansfield]]: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; [[Rob Stoner]]: bass; [[Howard Wyeth|Howie Wyeth]]: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || \n|-\n| 3 || ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' || 1978 || Hughes Stadium || 23/05/1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, Scarlet Rivera: violin; T-bone J. Henry Burnett: guitar, piano; Steven Soles: guitar; Mick Ronson: guitar; Bobby Neuwirth: guitar, vocals; Roger McGuinn: guitar, vocals; David Mansfield: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; Rob Stoner: bass; Howie Wyeth: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || Previously released on ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''. ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' was released in 1978 in Japan, Australia, and New Zealand.\n|-\n| 4 || ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' || 1991 || [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]] || 19/09/1974 || 4 (remake) - with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass. Organ overdub by [[Paul Griffin]].<refname=\"Heylin2010\" /> || \n|-\n| 5 || ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' || 2018 || A&R Studios|| 19/09/1974 || 4 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 6 || rowspan=\"9\" | ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]] (Deluxe edition)'' || rowspan=\"9\" | 2018 || A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 1 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 7 || A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 1 (remake) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 8 ||  A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 3 (with insert) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 9 ||  A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 5 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 10 || A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 6 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 11 || A&R Studios || 19/09/1974 || Rehearsal and Takes 1-3, Remake || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 12 || A&R Studios || 19/09/1974 || 4 (remake) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 13 || A&R Studios || 19/09/1974 || 4 (remake) - with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || Previously released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]''\n|-\n| 14 || Sound 80 || 27/12/1974 ||  || \"Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; Billy Peterson: bass; Bill Berg: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''\n|}\n\n==Covers==\n[[Mary Lee's Corvette]] covered the entire ''Blood on The Tracks'' album in 2002, including Idiot Wind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/mary-lees-corvette-blood-on-the-tracks-28113/ |title=Mary Lee's Corvette \u2013 Blood on the Tracks |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 February 2003 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Covers of Idiot Wind were also included on [[Phil Pritchett]]'s album ''Blueprint Garage Volume 2''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deezer.com/en/track/77303011 |title=Idiot Wind: Phil Pritchett |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=deezer.com |publisher=Deezer |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Coal Porters]] album ''How Dark This Earth Will Shine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |title=Bob Dylan \u2013 Uncut January 2005 CDs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2004 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original cast recording of ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]'', recorded at [[Abbey Road Studios]], includes the song.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oldvictheatre.com/news/2017/08/the-girl-from-the-north-country-cast-recording |title=The Girl from the North Country cast recording is here |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 August 2017 |website=oldvictheatre.com |publisher=The Old Vic |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind Lyrics]\n*[http://www.bjorner.com/songsi.htm#_Toc532968701 Cover versions (bjorner.com)]\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Dylan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|the Swedish artist|Amanda Bergman}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Idiot Wind\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blood on the Tracks]]\n| released = January 1975\n| recorded = 27 December 1974\n| studio   = [[Sound 80]],<br>[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\n| venue    = \n| genre    = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length   = 7:48\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| tracks   = {{Blood on the Tracks tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Idiot Wind'''\" is a song by [[Bob Dylan]], which appeared on his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.  The song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year. Dylan recorded the song in September 1974, but as with some other songs from ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'', re-recorded it in December 1974. Between the recordings, he often reworked the lyrics. A live version of the song was released on Dylan's 1976 album ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'', and all of the studio outtakes from the September sessions were released on the deluxe edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' in 2018.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nThe song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year and a separation from Sara Lowndes, who he had married in 1965. Dylan had moved to a farm in Minnesota with his brother, David Zimmerman and there started to write the songs that were recorded for his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.<ref name=\"UNCUT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656/ |title=Shelter From The Storm \u2013 the inside story of Bob Dylan's Blood on the Tracks |last=Hasted |first=Nick |date=15 November 2013 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011356/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the Spring of 1974, Dylan had taken art classes at [[Carnegie Hall]] and was influenced by his tutor [[Norman Raeben]].<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Rogovoy2009\">{{cite book|author=Seth Rogovoy|title=Bob Dylan: Prophet, Mystic, Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdbgeObYgIkC&pg=PA160|date=24 November 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-5983-2|pages=160\u2013}}</ref> and, in particular, Raeben's view of [[time]].<ref name=\"GillOdegard2004\">{{cite book|author1=Andy Gill|author2=Kevin Odegard|title=A Simple Twist of Fate: Bob Dylan and the Making of Blood on the Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tt0HAQAAMAAJ|date=January 2004|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-81231-6}}</ref> Dylan was later to say that Idiot Wind was \"a song I wanted to make as a painting.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\">{{cite book|author=Bill Flanagan|title=Written in My Soul: Conversations with Rock's Great Songwriters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|date=1 April 2010|publisher=RosettaBooks|isbn=978-0-7953-1081-2|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506011534/https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Idiot Wind\" was a derogatory phrase employed by Raeben and this may have inspired Dylan's use of it, although the term also appears in the poem \"June 1940\" by [[Weldon Kees]] and that may have been the reference point.<ref name=\"Wilentz2011\">{{cite book|author=Sean Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sb5UygkZlH0C&pg=PA140|date=15 February 2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4070-7411-5|pages=140\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDylan first recorded \"Idiot Wind\" in New York City on 12 September 1974 during the initial ''Blood on the Tracks'' sessions at [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]]. The first recording included just guitar and bass, with organ later [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]]. That December, working from a suggestion from his brother that the album should have a more commercial sound, Dylan re-recorded half the songs on ''Blood on the Tracks'', including \"Idiot Wind\", in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /><ref name=\"OHAGAN\">{{cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Sean |title=The raw, painful birth of Blood on the Tracks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417055617/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks Review |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |work=BBC |year=2007 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919065715/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |archive-date=19 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Creswell2007\">{{cite book|author=Toby Creswell|title=1001 Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bhYnNaM0zEUC&pg=PA24|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing|isbn=1-74273-148-1|pages=24\u2013}}</ref> The New York sessions were engineered by [[Phil Ramone]]. In New York, Dylan's guitar was tuned to [[Open D tuning|open D]] with a [[capo]] on the second [[fret]] so that all of the songs were in the [[Key (music)|key]] of E.<ref name=\"Wise2017\">{{cite book|author=Wise Publications|title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEejDgAAQBAJ|date=8 April 2017|publisher=Wise Publications|isbn=978-1-78323-916-0}}</ref> Paul Martinson was the engineer for the Minneapolis sessions.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" />\n\nThe re-recorded versions were radical departures from the original recordings, and each new recording included changes to the lyrics from the earlier versions.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /><ref name=\"Dalton2012\">{{cite book|author=David Dalton|title=Who Is That Man? In Search of the Real Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SDcDAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT346|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-779-2|pages=346\u2013}}</ref> The September 1974 recording of Idiot Wind featured just acoustic guitar and bass instrumentation, whereas the re-recording made on 27 December 1974 and issued on ''Blood on the Tracks'', featured a full band. This group of local musicians had been hurriedly been put together, and Dylan had not previously met them.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"AMSO\" /> The Minneapolis recordings are in [[standard tuning]].<ref name=\"Wise2017\" /> [[Clinton Heylin]] recounts that Dylan frequently reworked the song from September to December.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Still on the Road: The Songs of Bob Dylan Vol. 2 1974-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaSeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84901-494-6|pages=55\u2013}}</ref> In a 1991 interview with [[Paul Zollo]], Dylan said that there could be many more verses for the song and that it could be constantly reworked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn\u2019t stop. It wouldn\u2019t stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It\u2019s something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref> Zollo contrasts the ''Blood on the Tracks'' version with the one from ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' which was Take 4, with added organ overdubs, recorded on 19 September 1974 in New York, and opines that the gentler delivery of the song in the September version \"makes the inherent disquiet of the song even more disturbing.\"<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\" /><ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |title=Read the complete tracklisting for Bob Dylan\u2019s More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=20 September 2018 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBarbara O'Dair (2009) links the song to two of Dylan's other compositions, \"Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands\" (1966) and \"Sara\" (1976) as a set of songs written across ten years \"addressing a woman that bears a resemblance to his now ex-wife Sara Lowndes.\" O'Dair criticises the song for [[victim blaming]].<ref name=\"ODAIR2009\">{{cite book |last=O'Dair |first=Barbara |editor-last1=Dettmar |editor-first1=Kevin |title=The Cambridge Companion to Bob Dylan |page= 83 |chapter=Bob Dylan and gender politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73eAjOofhCAC|date=19 February 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82843-7}}</ref> avid Goldblatt and Edward Necarsulmer (2011) say that in the song, Dylan \"explores the bitterness of resentment and revenge against a lover and against one's own love who botched their love.\"<ref name=\"PVI2011\">{{cite book |last1=Goldblatt |first1=David |last2=Necarsulmer IV |first2=Edward |editor-last1=Porter |editor-first1=Carl J. |editor-last2=Vernezze |editor-first2=Peter |editor-last3=Irwin |editor-first3=William |title=Bob Dylan and Philosophy: It's Alright Ma (I'm Only Thinking) |publisher=Open Court |date=2011 |page=163 |chapter=Language on the Lam(b): Tarantula in Dylan and Nietzsche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JaOqtb977hQC |isbn=978-0-8126-9760-5 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> Dylan has denied that the song is personal, stating in 1985 that:<ref name=\"WILLMAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |title=Dylan's blood-best album: 40 facts about the 40-year-old Blood On The Tracks |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=21 January 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405155031/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I thought I might have gone a little bit too far with 'Idiot Wind'\u2026 I didn't really think I was giving away too much; I thought that it seemed so personal that people would think it was about so-and-so who was close to me. It wasn't \u2026 I didn't feel that one was too personal, but I felt it seemed too personal. Which might be the same thing, I don't know.\"}}\n\nTimothy Hampton takes the song as political, and a commentary on the [[Vietnam War]],<ref name=\"Hampton2019\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Hampton|title=Bob Dylan's Poetics: How the Songs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51WRDwAAQBAJ|date=26 March 2019|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-1-942130-15-4}}</ref> whereas David Dalton feels that Dylan draws parallels between his personal situation and the national one, and \"turns his own fate into an allegory of the soured American dream.\"<ref name=\"Dalton2012\" />\n\nDylan and Lowndes' relationship deteriorated in 1976, and David Kinney relates how Dylan played Idiot Wind in a 1976 show at Fort Collins whilst Lowndes was in the audience, noting in the following sentence that the pair were divorced the following year.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" /> \n\nIndividual outtakes from the New York sessions were released in 1991 on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' and in 2018 on the single-CD and 2-LP versions of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', while the complete New York sessions were released on the deluxe edition of the latter album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The deluxe version of  ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'' also included a remix of the December 1974 master issued on ''Blood on the Tracks''.<ref name=\"MBMTREL\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''.<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album ''Blood on the Tracks'' received mixed reviews on release.<ref name=\"Williamson2004\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Williamson|title=The Rough Guide to Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R2c8AQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-139-5}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' carried two reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/10-classic-albums-rolling-stone-originally-panned-101316/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-1975-101880/ |title=10 Classic Albums Rolling Stone Originally Panned  |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=25 July 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jonathan Cott described the album as \"magnificent and memorable\" and Idiot Wind, which he saw as equally as accomplished as the other songs, as \"explosive and bitter.\" Cott observed that it was the first time that Dylan had included himself in a condemnation in one of his songs, with the line \"We\u2019re idiots, babe/It's a wonder we can even feed ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-55031/  |title=Bob Dylan: Blood on the Tracks  |last=Cott |first=Jonathan |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, in the other ''Rolling Stone'' review, [[Jon Landau]] disparaged \"the childishness (without any redeeming childlike wonder) of so much of Idiot Wind.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |title=Blood on the Tracks |last=Landau |first=Jon |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230122112/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lester Bangs]] originally regarded the song as \"absurdly spiteful\" and was unimpressed, although he soon found himself listening to the album frequently.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2003 book ''[[Dylan's Visions of Sin]]'', [[Christopher Ricks|Professor Christopher Ricks]] discusses a particular lyrical couplet from the song, namely: \"Blowing like a circle around my skull/From the [[Grand Coulee Dam]] to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]].\" Ricks praises this as \"fierce \u2026 And it's a true rhyme because of the metaphorical relation, because of what a head of state is, and the body politic, and because of the relation of the Capitol to the skull (another of those white domes), with which it disconcertingly rhymes. An imperfect rhyme, perfectly judged.\"<ref name=\"Ricks2011\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlDWua9p8lEC|date=5 May 2011|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-0-85786-202-0}}</ref> The same rhyme had impressed [[Allen Ginsberg]], who wrote to Dylan comparing it to an image from [[The Bridge (long poem)|The Bridge]] by [[Hart Crane]]. Dylan was apparently gratified to receive Ginsberg's letter, and it was a contributing factor in leading to Ginsberg being invited onto the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/on-the-road-with-bob-dylan-joan-baez-and-the-rolling-thunder-revue-183508/ |title=On the Road With Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the Rolling Thunder Revue  |last=Hentoff |first=Nat |date=15 January 1976 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In his 1976 review in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Paul Cowan also referred to these lyrics, saying that they evoked both [[Woody Guthrie]] in the language used and [[T.S. Elliot]] in the delivery of the vocal. Like Cott, Cowan noted the ultimately self-accusatory nature of the lyrics, which he felt provided a surprising conclusion to the song.<ref name=\"COWAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |title=Riffs: Bob Dylan\u2019s Pain \u2014 Flip Side of Cruelty |last=Cowan |first=Paul |date=3 February 1975 |work=The Village Voice |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316142900/https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lyrics referencing the Capitol replaced the earlier \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your jaw/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the [[Mardi Gras]]\" used in New York.<ref name=\"Burger2018\">{{cite book|author=Jeff Burger|title=Dylan on Dylan: Interviews and Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT257|date=1 May 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-0-912777-44-3|pages=257\u2013}}</ref> Zollo also felt that this pair of lines was the highlight of the song.<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\">{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn\u2019t stop. It wouldn\u2019t stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It\u2019s something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[1001 Songs]]'', [[Toby Creswell]] says that the track is an \"epic of elegantly phrased bile\" and is \"not based on logical exposition.\"<ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /> The song was 16th on '' [[American Songwriter]]'' magazine's 2009 ranking of ''The 30 Greatest Dylan Songs''.<ref name=\"AMSO\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-16-idiot-wind/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #16, \"Idiot Wind\"|author=Schlansky, Evan|date=20 April 2009|publisher=americansongwriter.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and placed fourth in Jim Beviglia's 2013 book ''Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs''.<ref name=\"Beviglia2013\">{{cite book|author=Jim Beviglia|title=Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRMeAAAAQBAJ|date=11 July 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8824-1}}</ref>\n\nWhen Dylan won the [[Nobel prize for literature]] in 2016, ''[[The Guardian]]'' cited \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your teeth/ You\u2019re an idiot, babe/ It's a wonder that you still know how to breathe\" from Idiot Wind as one of his greatest lyrics.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Are these the lyrics that won Bob Dylan a Nobel prize? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521040933/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |archive-date=21 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', Sean O'Hagan remarked of the song \"By turns paranoid, derisory and vengeful, it is a dark masterpiece of venomous intent, a great part of its raw power resting in the very discomfort the listener feels as it gathers momentum and the tone becomes ever more bitter.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Live Performances==\nDylan played the song live 55 times between 18 April 1976, when it was first included in his set, at Civic Centre, Lakeland, Florida; and 30 August 1992 when he played it at the Orpheum Theatre, Minneapolis. 1976 and 1992 were the only years in which it featured in his live shows. As of April 2020, he has not performed it live since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Clinton Heylin]], a prolific author of material about Dylan, flew from England to California to attend Dylan's shows when he heard that Idiot Wind was being played live again.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nArtist Mohammad Omer Khalil produced a series of etchings, inspired by Dylan's music, that were displayed at the [[National Museum of African Art]] in 1994, including one entitled Idiot Wind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africa.si.edu/collections/view/objects/asitem/People@120/2?t:state:flow=847c62c4-c3b4-469a-baaf-52952b9c28ed |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=africa.si.edu |publisher=National Museum of African Art |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of the lyrics of Idiot Wind are mentioned in the 1995 song \"[[Only Wanna Be with You]]\" by American band [[Hootie & the Blowfish]]. The use of Dylan's lyrics reportedly led to an out-of-court settlement, with Dylan receiving money from Hootie & the Blowfish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|title=Darius Rucker on 'Wagon Wheel' and the Future of Hootie|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=19 July 2013|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023200015/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSwedish musician [[Amanda Bergman]] used to perform under the stage name ''Idiot Wind''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|title = The shark that became Jaw Lesson is now Idiot Wind|date = 13 September 2010|website = svt.se|publisher = Swedish Television|last = Beckman|first = Eva|language = Swedish|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426205311/http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|archivedate = 26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a question on the \"Ask Lou\" section of his website in 2007, singer-songwriter [[Lou Reed]] cited \"Idiot Wind\" as the song he wished he had written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |work=loureed.com |title=Ask Lou |date=December 2007 |access-date=12 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415130637/http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |archive-date=15 April 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Novelist [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] included Idiot Wind as one of his eight records for [[Desert Island Discs]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |title=Peter Carey |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 2008 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in the play ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]''. In the original London production, it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Richard |title=Girl from the North Country lets us hear Bob Dylan's mysteries anew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 January 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150058/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> who won the 2018 Laurence Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Musical for her role.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Olivier Awards 2018: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930235126/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |archive-date=30 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nPeter Kaldheim's 2019 novel ''Idiot Wind: A Memoir'' was published by Canongate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|title=Idiot Wind by Peter Kaldheim \u2013 Canongate Books|website=canongate.co.uk|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715152051/https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |title=In Idiot Wind, a Lost Soul Finds His Way Home |last=Williams |first=John |date=28 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729233051/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |archive-date=29 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\nThe officially released versions of the song on Bob Dylan albums are below.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" /><ref name=\"MBMTREL\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |title=1976 soon to be divorced |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |title=Still on the road: 1976 Rolling Thunder Revue II |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  !! Album !! Release Year !! Recorded at !! Recording date !! [[Take]] !! Personnel !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || ''[[Blood On The Tracks]]'' || 1975 || [[Sound 80]] || 27/12/1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums ||\n|-\n| 2 || ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'' || 1976 || [[Sonny Lubick Field at Hughes Stadium|Hughes Stadium]] || 23/05/1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, [[Scarlet Rivera]]: violin; [[T Bone Burnett|T-bone J. Henry Burnett]]: guitar, piano; [[Steven Soles]]: guitar; [[Mick Ronson]]: guitar; [[Bob Neuwirth|Bobby Neuwirth]]: guitar, voc